description: A muscle organ that attaches to a tail vertebra.
synonyms: ["caudal muscle","muscle organ of post-vent region","muscle organ of tail","post-vent region muscle organ","tail muscle","tail muscle organ"]

name: upper jaw molar
description: A molar tooth that is part of a upper jaw.
synonyms: ["molar tooth of upper jaw","upper jaw molar tooth","upper molar tooth"]

name: lower jaw molar
description: A molar tooth that is part of a lower jaw.
synonyms: ["lower jaw molar tooth","lower molar tooth","molar tooth of lower jaw"]

name: synovial bursa
description: A small fluid-filled sac lined by synovial membrane with an inner capillary layer of slimy fluid. It provides a cushion between bones and tendons and/or muscles around a joint. This helps to reduce friction between the bones and allows free movement. Bursae are filled with synovial fluid and are found around most major joints of the body.

name: fascia lata
description: The deep fascia of the thigh..

name: smegma
description: A combination of exfoliated (shed) epithelial cells, transudated skin oils, and moisture. It occurs in both female and male mammalian genitalia.

name: anterior cruciate ligament of knee joint
description: A major stabilizing ligament in the knee that attaches the surfaces of the femur and tibia.

name: dentition
description: A collection of teeth arranged in some pattern in the mouth or other part of the body. The arrangement may be a simple row, a collection of rows, or a more elaborate structure, such as a toooth whorl.

name: cuspid
description: A tooth that is typically long and pointed and bearing a single cusp.

name: tooth crown
description: The portion of the tooth covered by enamel.

name: patellar ligament
description: The central portion of the common tendon of the quadriceps femoris. It is attached to the apex of the PATELLA and to the lower part of the tubercle of the TIBIA.
synonyms: ["central band of tendon of quadriceps femoris","ligamentum patella"]

name: tooth root
description: The part of a tooth that is implanted in the gum; the root is normally located below the neck of the tooth, covered by cementum rather than enamel, and attached by the periodontal ligament to the alveolar bone

name: mouth floor
description: The ventral area of the mouth. In organisms with a tongue, this is the area under the ventral surface of the tongue.
synonyms: ["floor of mouth","floor of oval cavity","floor of the oval cavity"]

name: posterior cruciate ligament of knee joint
masticatory muscle
description: In humans: Muscles arising in the zygomatic arch that close the jaw. Their nerve supply is masseteric from the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve. (From Stedman, 25th ed)

name: palatal muscle
description: The muscles of the palate are the glossopalatine, palatoglossus, levator palati(ni), musculus uvulae, palatopharyngeus, and tensor palati(ni).
synonyms: ["muscle of palate","musculi palati mollis et faucium","palatal muscle","palate muscle","palatine muscle"]

name: rotator cuff
description: A group of muscles and their tendons that act to stabilize the shoulder. The four muscles of the rotator cuff are over half of the seven scapulohumeral muscles

name: abdominal cavity
description: The part of the ventral body cavity that is within the abdomen proper (excluding the pelvic cavity).
synonyms: ["cavity of abdominal compartment","cavity of compartment of abdomen","space of abdominal compartment"]

name: cranial suture
description: Fibrous joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages of the skull are connected by sutural ligaments (scant amount of collagenous dense connective tissue). Examples: sagittal suture, frontal suture.
synonyms: ["cranium suture","sutura","suture","suture joint of skull","suture of cranium"]

name: tooth socket
description: Dental alveolus (plural, alveoli) are sockets in the jaws in which the roots of teeth are held in the alveolar process of maxilla with the periodontal ligament. The lay term for dental alveoli is tooth sockets. A joint that connect the roots of the teeth and the alveolus are called gomphosis (plural gomphoses). In mammals, tooth sockets are found in the maxilla and the mandible..

name: foramen magnum
description: In anatomy, in the occipital bone, the foramen magnum is one of the several oval or circular apertures in the base of the skull, through which the medulla oblongata (an extension of the spinal cord) enters and exits the skull vault. Apart from the transmission of the medulla oblongata and its membranes, the foramen magnum transmits the Spinal Accessory nerve, vertebral arteries, the anterior and posterior spinal arteries, the membrana tectoria and alar ligaments..

name: omentum
description: A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.

name: sella turcica
description: The sella turcica is a saddle-shaped depression in the sphenoid bone at the base of the human skull..

name: fused sacrum
description: A collection of sacral vertebrae in the sacral region that are fused and part of the bony pelvis.
synonyms: ["os sacrum [vertebrae sacrales I - V]","sacrum","sacrum [sacral vertebrae I - V]","sacrum [sacral vertebrae I-V]"]

name: epidural space
description: The outermost part of the spinal canal. It is the space within the canal (formed by the surrounding vertebrae) lying outside the dura mater.

name: acromioclavicular joint
description: Any joint connecting the acromonion of the scapula and clavicle.

name: retroperitoneal space
description: Anatomical space in the abdominal cavity behind (retro) the peritoneum. It has no specific delineating anatomical structures. Organs are retroperitoneal if they only have peritoneum on their anterior side.

name: atlanto-axial joint
description: The Atlanto-axial joint is of a complicated nature, comprising no fewer than four distinct joints. There is a pivot articulation between the odontoid process of the axis and the ring formed by the anterior arch and the transverse ligament of the atlas.

name: metacarpophalangeal joint
description: The metacarpophalangeal joints (MCP) are of the condyloid kind, formed by the reception of the rounded heads of the metacarpal bones into shallow cavities on the proximal ends of the first phalanges, with the exception of that of the thumb, which presents more of the characters of a ginglymoid joint. Arthritis of the MCP is a distinguishing feature of Rheumatoid Arthritis, as opposed to the distal interphalangeal joint in osteoarthritis..

name: metatarsophalangeal joint
description: The metatarsophalangeal articulations are the joints between the metatarsal bones of the foot and the proximal bones of the toes . They are condyloid joints meaning an elliptical or rounded surface (of the metatarsal bones) come close to the shallow cavities (of the proximal phalanges). The ligaments are the plantar and two collateral.

name: abdominal wall
description: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.
synonyms: ["paries abdominalis","wall of abdomen","wall of abdomen proper"]

name: subtalar joint
description: A joint of the pes that connects the talus and the calcaneus.

name: pubic symphysis
description: The firm fibrocartilaginous joint in the median plane between the two opposing surfaces of the pubic bones, which are united by an interpubic disc of fibrocartilage as well as the superior and arcuate pubic ligaments.

name: temporomandibular joint
description: A synovial joint of the jaw that connects the mandible to the temporal bone.

name: calcaneal tendon
description: The Achilles tendon is a tendon of the posterior leg. It serves to attach the plantaris, gastrocnemius (calf) and soleus muscles to the calcaneus (heel) bone.
synonyms: ["Achille's tendon","Achilles tendon","Achilles' tendon","calcaneal tendon","tendo Achillis","tendo calcaneus"]

name: inguinal canal
description: the passage in the lower abdominal wall through which the spermatic cord in the male or the round ligament in the female, nerves and vessels pass from the pelvic cavity to the scrotum or labia majora, respectively

name: extrahepatic bile duct
description: Passages external to the liver for the conveyance of bile. These include the common bile duct and the common hepatic duct.

name: intrahepatic bile duct
description: Passages within the liver for the conveyance of bile. Includes right and left hepatic ducts even though these may join outside the liver to form the common hepatic duct.

name: Meckel's diverticulum
description: A small bulge in the small intestine present at birth. It is a vestigial remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct

name: laryngeal vocal fold
description: Either of two pairs of folds of mucous membrane projecting into the larynx.

name: sinus of Valsalva
description: one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.

name: carotid sinus
description: A localized dilation of the internal carotid artery at its origin, the common carotid artery bifurcation.

name: circle of Willis
description: A circle of arteries that supply blood to the brain. The Circle of Willis comprises the following arteries: Anterior cerebral artery (left and right); Anterior communicating artery; Internal carotid artery (left and right); Posterior cerebral artery (left and right); Posterior communicating artery (left and right).The basilar artery and middle cerebral arteries, supplying the brain, are also considered part of the circle
synonyms: ["arterial circle","arterial circle of Willis","cerebral arterial circle"]

name: vasa vasorum
description: Nutrient blood vessels which supply the walls of large arteries or veins.

name: brachiocephalic vein
description: The left and right brachiocephalic veins in the upper chest are formed by the union of each corresponding internal jugular vein and subclavian vein. This is at the level of the sternoclavicular joint. These great vessels merge to form the superior vena cava. The brachiocephalic veins are the major veins returning blood to the superior vena cava.

name: cavernous sinus
description: The cavernous sinus (or lateral sellar compartment), within the human head, is a large collection of thin-walled veins creating a cavity bordered by the temporal bone of the skull and the sphenoid bone, lateral to the sella turcica.

name: splenic vein
description: A vein arising from the splenic trabecular vein in the hilum of the spleen that drains into the portal vein.

name: neural tissue
description: Portion of tissue in the nervous system which consists of neurons and glial cells, and may also contain parts of the vasculature.

name: splanchnic nerve
description: The major nerves supplying sympathetic innervation to the abdomen, including the greater, lesser, and lowest (or smallest) splanchnic nerves that are formed by preganglionic fibers from the spinal cord which pass through the paravertebral ganglia and then to the celiac ganglia and plexuses and the lumbar splanchnic nerves carry fibers which pass through the lumbar paravertebral ganglia to the mesenteric and hypogastric ganglia.

name: recurrent laryngeal nerve
description: A branch of the vagus nerve that supplies motor function and sensation to the larynx (voice box). It travels within the endoneurium. It is the nerve of the 6th Branchial Arch.
synonyms: ["nervus laryngeus recurrens","recurrent laryngeal nerve from vagus nerve","recurrent nerve","vagus X nerve recurrent laryngeal branch"]

name: muscle spindle
description: The sensory organs in muscle that are involved in the stretch reflex.

name: Pacinian corpuscle
description: Any of the rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors found in subcutaneous tissue beneath both hairy and glabrous skin, and which normally contain an afferent nerve fiber surrounded by a capsule with multiple concentric layers.
synonyms: ["corpuscle of golgi-mazzoni","corpusculum lamellosum","golgi-mazzoni corpuscle","lamellar corpuscle","Pacinian corpuscle"]

name: anterior cranial fossa
description: The floor of the anterior fossa is formed by the orbital plates of the frontal, the cribriform plate of the ethmoid, and the small wings and front part of the body of the sphenoid; it is limited behind by the posterior borders of the small wings of the sphenoid and by the anterior margin of the chiasmatic groove. The lesser wings of the sphenoid separate the anterior and middle fossae.

name: lingual nerve
description: The lingual nerve is a branch of the mandibular nerve (CN V3), itself a branch of the trigeminal nerve, which supplies sensory innervation to the tongue. It also carries fibers from the facial nerve, which return taste information from the anterior two thirds of the tongue.
synonyms: ["lingual branch of trigeminal nerve","trigeminal nerve lingual branch","trigeminal V nerve lingual branch"]

name: middle cranial fossa
description: The compartment containing the anterior extremities and half the inferior surface of the temporal lobes (TEMPORAL LOBE) of the cerebral hemispheres. Lying posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa (CRANIAL FOSSA, ANTERIOR), it is formed by part of the TEMPORAL BONE and SPHENOID BONE. It is separated from the posterior cranial fossa (CRANIAL FOSSA, POSTERIOR) by crests formed by the superior borders of the petrous parts of the temporal bones. The middle fossa, deeper than the anterior cranial fossa, is narrow medially and widens laterally to the sides of the skull. It is separated from the posterior fossa by the clivus and the petrous crest. It is bounded in front by the posterior margins of the lesser wings of the sphenoid bone, the anterior clinoid processes, and the ridge forming the anterior margin of the chiasmatic groove; behind, by the superior angles of the petrous portions of the temporal bones and the dorsum sellC&; laterally by the temporal squamC&, sphenoidal angles of the parietals, and greater wings of the sphenoid. It is traversed by the squamosal, sphenoparietal, sphenosquamosal, and sphenopetrosal sutures.

name: vestibular nerve
description: The vestibular nerve is one of the two branches of the Vestibulocochlear nerve (the cochlear nerve being the other). It goes to the semicircular canals via the vestibular ganglion. It receives positional information. Axons of the vestibular nerve synapse in the vestibular nucleus on the lateral floor and wall of the fourth ventricle in the pons and medulla. It arises from bipolar cells in the vestibular ganglion, ganglion of Scarpa, which is situated in the upper part of the outer end of the internal auditory meatus..
synonyms: ["vestibular root of acoustic nerve","vestibular root of eighth cranial nerve","vestibulocochlear VIII nerve vestibular component"]

name: musculocutaneous nerve
description: a large branch of the brachial plexus supplying various parts of the upper arm (as flexor muscles) and forearm (as the skin).

name: cervical nerve plexus
description: An arrangement of nerve fibers, running from the spine that travels to the head and neck where it innervates skin and muscle.

name: thoracic nerve
description: The twelve spinal nerves on each side of the thorax. They include eleven INTERCOSTAL NERVES and one subcostal nerve. Both sensory and motor, they supply the muscles and skin of the thoracic and abdominal walls.

name: intercostal nerve
description: The intercostal nerves are the anterior divisions (rami anteriores; ventral divisions) of the thoracic spinal nerves from T1 to T11. Each nerve is connected with the adjoining ganglion of the sympathetic trunk by a gray and a white ramus communicans. The intercostal nerves are distributed chiefly to the thoracic pleura and abdominal peritoneum and differ from the anterior divisions of the other spinal nerves in that each pursues an independent course without plexus formation. The first two nerves supply fibers to the upper limb in addition to their thoracic branches; the next four are limited in their distribution to the parietes of the thorax; the lower five supply the parietes of the thorax and abdomen. The 7th intercostal nerve terminates at the xyphoid process, at the lower end of the sternum. The 10th intercostal nerve terminates at the umbilicus. The twelfth thoracic is distributed to the abdominal wall and groin..
synonyms: ["anterior ramus of thoracic nerve","anterior ramus of thoracic spinal nerve","ramus anterior, nervus thoracicus","thoracic anterior ramus","ventral ramus of thoracic spinal nerve"]

name: mediastinum
description: The central part of the thoracic cavity enclosed by the left and right pleurae.

name: mouth mucosa
description: A mucous membrane that lines the mouth.
synonyms: ["mouth mucosa","mouth mucous membrane","mouth organ mucosa","mucosa of mouth","mucous membrane of mouth","oral mucous membrane","oral part of viscerocranial mucosa","tunica mucosa oris"]

name: prostate bud
description: A region of the fetal urogenital sinus epithelium destined to become the prostate.

name: metapodium bone
description: A bone of the metapodial skeleton
synonyms: ["metacarpal or metatarsal bone","metacarpal/metatarsal","metacarpal/metatarsal bone","metapodi bone","metapodial bone","metapodium bone"]

name: forelimb stylopod
description: The part of the forelimb between pectoral region and the elbow, corresponding to the humerus.

name: intraembryonic coelom
description: The part of the coelom in the embryo between the somatopleuric and splanchnopleuric mesoderm; the principal body cavities of the trunk (thoracic, abdominal, and pelvic) arise from this embryonic part of the coelom

name: extraembryonic coelomic cavity
description: the fluid-filled spaces formed within the mass of extraembryonic mesoderm that later fuse to become a large extraembryonic cavity

name: fallopian tube
description: Initial section of the oviduct through which the ova pass from the ovary to the uterus

name: Mullerian duct
description: paired ducts of the embryo that run down the lateral sides of the urogenital ridge and terminate at the mullerian eminence in the primitive urogenital sinus. In the female, they will develop to form the fallopian tubes, uterus, and the upper portion of the vagina; in the male, they are lost. These ducts are made of tissue of mesodermal origin. develops either by lengthwise splitting of the archinephric duct (in chondrichthyans and some amphibians) or by a elongated invagination of the coelomic epithelium (other vertebrates) In males, the oviducts regress. The cranial end of the oviduct maintains an opening into the coelom (which primitively may have been the anteriormost coelomic funnels connecting the nephrocoel with the coelom). This opening is the ostium tubae.

name: stroma
description: Connective, non-functional supportive framework of a biological cell, tissue, or organ. Contrast with parenchyma.

name: capsule
description: A cover or envelope partly or wholly surrounding a structure. Examples: egg shell, articular capsules, renal capsules.

name: liver primordium
description: A small endodermal thickening in the foregut adjacent to the transverse septum. Invaginates forming the hepatic diverticulum.

name: hypaxial myotome region

name: axial muscle

name: horizontal septum
description: A logitudinal sheet of continuous connective tissue partition developing at the apex of the chevron-shaped myotome and separating dorsal (epaxial) and ventral (hypaxial) body wall muscle masses; each is destined to become, respectively, the epaxial and hyopaxial musculature.

name: retinal neural layer

name: bursa of Fabricius
description: An epithelial and lymphoid organ that develops as a dorsal diverticulum of the proctodeal region of the cloaca in birds. The luminal (interior) surface of the bursa is plicated with as many as 15 primary and 7 secondary plicae or folds. These plicae have hundreds of bursal follicles containing follicle-associated epithelial cells, lymphocytes, macrophages, and plasma cells. Lymphoid stem cells migrate from the fetal liver to the bursa during ontogeny. In the bursa, these stem cells acquire the characteristics of mature, immunocompetent B cells. The bursa is an organ found in birds involved in B cell differentiation.

name: bursal plica
description: Follicle containing part of bursa of Fabricius. The luminal (interior) surface of the bursa is plicated with as many as 15 primary and 7 secondary plicae or folds. These plicae have hundreds of bursal follicles containing follicle-associated epithelial cells, lymphocytes, macrophages, and plasma cells. Lymphoid stem cells migrate from the fetal liver to the bursa during ontogeny. In the bursa, these stem cells acquire the characteristics of mature, immunocompetent B cells.

name: bursal follicle
description: Follicle within the plicae of bursa of Fabricius.

name: cardiac jelly
description: Portion of extracellular matrix between the myocardium and the endocardium. The cardiac jelly plays a central role in the septation of the heart and comprises most of the thickness of the heart wall at early stages, but disappears as the heart differentiates.

name: left atrioventricular canal
description: An atrioventricular canal that is in the left side of a atrioventricular region.

name: right atrioventricular canal
description: An atrioventricular canal that is in the right side of a atrioventricular region.

name: sinusoid
description: small blood vessel similar to a capillary but with a fenestrated endothelium. Sinusoids are found in the liver, lymphoid tissue, endocrine organs, and hematopoietic organs such as the bone marrow and the spleen. Sinusoids found within terminal villi of the placenta are not comparable to these; they possess a continuous endothelium and complete basal lamina.

name: splenic sinusoid

name: chitinous tooth

name: tooth-like structure

name: epithelial tube
description: Epithelial tubes transport gases, liquids and cells from one site to another and form the basic structure of many organs and tissues, with tube shape and organization varying from the single-celled excretory organ in Caenorhabditis elegans to the branching trees of the mammalian kidney and insect tracheal system.

name: endothelial tube

name: fat pad

name: arthropod fat body
description: An insect gland dorsal to the insect gut, with a function analogous to that of the vertebrate liver. It is a storage organ for fats, glycogen and protein and is a major site of intermediary metabolism.

name: kidney mesenchyme

name: transverse gyrus of Heschl
description: The area of the temporal lobe concerned with hearing. The transverse temporal gyri (also called Heschl's gyri or Heschl's convolutions) are found in the area of primary auditory cortex in the superior temporal gyrus of the human brain, occupying Brodmann areas 41 and 42. It is the first cortical structure to process incoming auditory information. Anatomically, the transverse temporal gyri are distinct in that they run mediolaterally (towards the center of the brain) rather than dorsiventrally (front to back) as all other temporal lobe gyri run. The Heschl's gyri are named after Richard L. Heschl.

name: brain ventricle/choroid plexus

name: blood-air barrier

name: posterior stroma of cornea

name: otic ganglion

name: prevertebral ganglion

name: sympathetic afferent fiber

name: gonial bone

name: cutaneous elastic tissue

name: peripheral lymph node

description: Fetally derived placental region that separates the maternal uterine tissue from the placenta labyrinth

name: nasal concha of ethmoid bone
description: One of the conchae of the ethmoid bone, which occupy the caudal part of the nasal fossae and form the lateral and superior portions of the turbinate bones in mammals. The ethmoturbinals are associated with the cribiform plate. They are covered with olfactory epithelium. Primarily, they serve to increase the surface area over which olfactory receptor neurons can come in contact with respiratory air. These olfactory receptor nerves then synapse with the mitral cells of the olfactory lobes through the cribiform plate in the manner described above
synonyms: ["ethmo-turbinate","ethmoturbinal","ethmoturbinate","nasal turbinate of ethmoid bone","turbinate of ethmoid bone"]

name: upper part of vagina
description: The upper third of the vagina.
synonyms: ["cranial vagina","pelvic part of vagina","vagina upper part"]

name: internal female genitalia
description: The internal feminine genital organs, including the ovaries, uterine tubes, uterus, uterine cervix, and vagina.
synonyms: ["female internal genitalia","internal female genital organ","internal genitalia of female reproductive system"]

name: saccule duct
description: The saccular portion of the utriculosaccular duct that normally extends from the sacculus to the endolymphatic duct

name: utricle duct
description: The utricular portion of the utriculosaccular duct that normally extends from the utriculus to the endolymphatic duct

name: utricle valve
description: The utriculo-endolymphatic (UE) valve which is located in the antero-inferior wall of the utricle at the orifice of the utricular duct and serves to regulate endolymph volume in the endolymphatic sac, the utricle and the canals

name: cerebellum fissure
description: One of a set of deep furrows which divide the lobules of the cerebellum. Examples: postcentral, primary and secondary furrows

name: primordial ovarian follicle
description: primordial follicles are indiscernible to the naked eye and develop to primary, secondary, and finally mature vesicular follicles

name: conus arteriosus
description: A conical pouch formed from the upper and left angle of the right ventricle in the chordate heart, from which the pulmonary artery arises. the anteriosuperior, smooth-walled portion of the cavity of the right ventricle, beginning at the supraventricular crest and terminates in the pulmonary trunk.

name: uterine tube infundibulum
description: The funnel-like expansion of the abdominal extremity of the uterine tube

name: major sublingual duct
description: The duct that drains the anterior portion of the sublingual gland and opens at the sublingual papilla

name: minor sublingual duct
description: Any of the 8-20 small ducts that open into the mouth on the surface of the sublingual fold

name: Hassall's corpuscle
description: The small spherical bodies of epithelial cells found in the medulla of the thymus, that are arranged in a concentric pattern around clusters of degenerating lymphocytes, eosinophils and macrophages

name: thymus corticomedullary boundary
description: The dense region demarcating the thymus medulla from the surrounding cortex that is characterized by numerous blood vessels (predominantly arterioles) with some perivascular connective tissue, mature and immature T lymphocytes, dendritic cells, variable numbers of perivascular B-lymphocytes and plasma cells; site of entry of bone marrow stem cells and exit of mature, functional T cells
synonyms: ["thymic cortico-medullary boundary","thymic corticomedullary boundary","thymic corticomedullary junction","thymic corticomedullary zone","thymus CMZ","thymus cortico-medullary boundary","thymus corticomedullary junction","thymus corticomedullary zone"]

name: medulla oblongata anterior median fissure
description: The longitudinal groove in the midline of the anterior aspect of the medulla oblongata
synonyms: ["anterior median fissure","anterior median fissure of medulla","anterior median fissure of medulla oblongata","fissura mediana anterior medullae oblongatae","ventral median fissure of medulla","ventral median sulcus"]

name: spinal cord motor column
description: The subclasses of motor neurons which are organized into longitudinally oriented columns that occupy distinct and, in some cases, discontinuous domains along the rostrocaudal axis of the spinal cord; motor neurons within a single column send their axons to a common peripheral target

name: fourth ventricle median aperture
description: The large midline opening of the posterior inferior part of the roof of the fourth ventricle that connects the fourth ventricle to the posterior cerebromedullary cistern and the spinal cord
synonyms: ["apertura mediana","foramen of Magendie","foramen of Majendie","fourth ventricle median aperture","median aperture","median aperture of fourth ventricle"]

name: fourth ventricle lateral aperture
description: One of the two lateral openings of the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space at the cerebellopontine angle.
synonyms: ["apertura lateralis","foramen of key and retzius","foramen of Key-Retzius","foramen of Luschka","foramen of Retzius","lateral aperture","lateral aperture of fourth ventricle"]

name: interventricular foramen of CNS
description: The paired channels that connect the lateral and third ventricles and allows cerebrospinal fluid produced in the lateral ventricles to flow into the third ventricles

name: pelvic ligament
description: The dorsal sacroiliac, the sacrotuberal and/or the iliolumbar ligaments associated with the bony ring formed by the pair of hip bones fused at the symphysis and their firm articulation with the sacrum

name: subarcuate fossa
description: The irregular depression found on the posterior inner surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone just below its crest and above and lateral to the internal acoustic meatus.

name: cervical vertebra 1 arcus anterior
description: The arch that connects the lateral masses of the atlas anteriorly and articulates with the anterior articular facet of the dens of the axis.
synonyms: ["anterior arch of atlas","arcus anterior","arcus anterior atlantis","cervical vertebra 1 arcus anterior"]

name: hyoid bone greater horn
description: The larger and more lateral of the paired processes on either side of the hyoid bone
synonyms: ["cornu majus","cornu majus ossis hyoidei","cornua majora","greater cornu","greater cornua","greater horn","greater horn of hyoid","greater horn of hyoid bone","tyrohal","tyrohals"]

name: hyoid bone lesser horn
description: shorter and more medial of the paired processes on either side of the hyoid bone
synonyms: ["cornu minus","cornu minus ossis hyoidei","lesser cornu","lesser cornu of hyoid","lesser cornua","lesser horn","lesser horn of hyoid","lesser horn of hyoid bone","lesser horn of the hyoid"]

name: hyoid bone body
description: The main curve of the hyoid bone, from which the horns extend

name: tarsal gland acinus
description: A sac-like structure comprising a sebaceous gland.

name: posterior lobe of cerebellum
description: The region of the cerebellum that is posterior to the primary fissure and anterior to the posteriolateral fissure
synonyms: ["cerebellar posterior lobe","cerebellum posterior lobe","middle lobe-1 of cerebellum","posterior cerebellar lobe","posterior lobe of cerebellum","posterior lobe of the cerebellum","posterior lobe-1 of cerebellum"]

name: cerebellum hemisphere lobule
description: The region of a cerebellar lobule that resides in either of the lateral sections of the cerebellum outside the vermis; in mammals, the vermis portion of the cerebellum has a foliation pattern along the AP axis that is distinct from the lateral cerebellar hemispheres
synonyms: ["cerebellar hemisphere lobule","lobule of cerebellar hemisphere","lobule of hemisphere of cerebellum"]

name: cerebellum lobule
description: one of the the ten gyri of the cerebellar cortex

name: cerebellum intermediate zone
description: The paired regions of the cerebellar hemisphere that lie adjacent to the vermis and are between the vermis and lateral regions of the hemispheres; it receives input from the corticopontocerebellar fibers that originate from the motor cortex, and also receives sensory feedback from the muscles; these signals are integrated by this region, to coordinate muscle activity with motor inputs
synonyms: ["cerebellar paravermis","cerebellar paravermis","cerebellum intermediate hemisphere","intermediate part of spinocerebellum","intermediate zone","paravermis"]

name: cerebellar plate
description: The embryonic pseudostratified epithelium of the fourth cerebellar ventricle that eventually forms the vermis and ventral neuroepithelium

name: cerebellum posterior vermis
description: The posterior portion of the narrow middle zone between the two hemispheres of the cerebellum that is located posterior to the primary fissure
synonyms: ["posterior cerebellum vermis","vermis lobus posterior","vermis of posterior lobe","vermis of posterior lobe of cerebellum","vermis of the posterior lobe of the cerebellum"]

name: primary muscle spindle
description: The sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and sensitive to stretch velocity

name: secondary muscle spindle
description: The sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and not sensitive to stretch velocity

name: golgi tendon organ
description: The sensory organ in muscle that is involved in regulating muscle tension

name: egg cylinder
description: The transient cup-like structure of the epiblast that consists of a single layer of embryonic cells

name: labium minora
description: One of the folds of skin which form the inner lips on both sides of the vaginal opening

name: embryonic-extraembryonic boundary
description: The connection between the embryo proper and extraembryonic tissues

name: dermatome
description: A transitional population of migrating mesenchymal cells that derive from somites and that will become dermal cells.

name: periocular mesenchyme
description: The mesenchymal cells that give rise to the corneal endothelium, corneal stroma, sclera, iris stroma, ciliary muscle, ciliary stroma, and trabecular meshwork of the eye.

name: baroreceptor
description: The sensory nerve endings in the wall of the atria of the heart, vena cava, aortic arch and carotid sinus that are sensitive to changes in blood pressure

name: obsolete embryonic cilium
description: OBSOLETE: the earliest cilia of the mouse embryo found on the cells of the embryonic node

name: spongiotrophoblast layer
description: The structure of the outer structural layer of the rodent placenta.

name: germinal neuroepithelium
description: The single layer of epithelial cells that lines the early neural tube and develops into the nervous system and into the neural crest cells

name: ganglionic eminence
description: The transient proliferative population of neurons that expands exponentially during late prenatal development; it is a continuous germinal zone distinct from the ventricular zone that surrounds the brain ventricles.
synonyms: ["embryonic GE","embryonic subventricular zone","embryonic SVZ","embryonic/fetal subventricular zone","fetal subventricular zone","GE","subependymal layer","subventricular zone","SVZ"]

name: medial ganglionic eminence
description: A distinct elevation of a transient proliferating cell mass of the fetal subventricular zone; this mass contributes most of its cells to the neocortex; however, hippocampal neurons, thalamus, septum and olfactory bulb neurons are also partly derived from the MGE.

name: lateral ganglionic eminence
description: A distinct elevation of a transient proliferating cell mass of the fetal subventricular zone; this mass contributes most of its cells to the striatum; however, neocortex, thalamus, septum and olfactory bulb neurons are also partly derived from the LGE

name: caudal ganglionic eminence
description: The caudally located, distinct elevation of a transient proliferating cell mass of the fetal subventricular zone, located adjacent to the lateral ventricle

name: chorionic plate
description: That portion of the chorionic wall in the region of its uterine attachment, which gives rise to chorionic villi; it consists of the mesoderm that lines the chorionic vesicle and, on the maternal side, of the trophoblast that lines the intervillous spaces; in the last half of gestation, the mesodermal connective tissue is largely replaced by fibrinoid material, and the amnionic membrane is adherent to the fetal side of the plate.

name: canal of Schlemm
description: The vascular structure encircling the anterior chamber of the eye, through which the aqueous humor is returned to the blood circulation
synonyms: ["Schlemm's canal","scleral sinus","scleral venous sinus","sinus venosus of sclera","sinus venosus sclerae"]

name: aqueous vein
description: A vessel that receives aqueous humor from the sinus venosus sclerae (canal of Schlemm)

name: head ectomesenchyme
description: mesenchymal cells derived from neural crest cells that contribute to development of the hard and soft tissue in the head and neck, including the branchial arches.

name: podocyte slit diaphragm
description: The thin membrane that covers the podocyte filtration slit which allows small molecules such as water, glucose, and ionic salts to pass through while retaining larger macromolecules in the bloodstream

name: podocyte slit junction
description: The gaps between the interdigitated foot processes of the podocyte

name: cutaneous microfibril
description: The fiber-like strand of fibrillin that forms the scaffold of the cutaneous elastic fibers found in the extracellular matrix of the skin

name: cortical subplate
description: The transient outer neural tube region that contains the first generated post-mitotic neurons that receive synaptic input from thalamic axons and in turn project axons to the developing cortical plate

name: obsolete retinal cone cell inner segment
description: The retinal cone cell region which contains the machinery of the cell (mitochondria, golgi, endoplasmic reticulum, etc) and where opsin molecules are assembled and passed to be part of the outer segment region

name: obsolete retinal cone cell outer segment
description: The retinal cone cell region in which the visual pigment rhodopsin is in invaginations of the cell membrane

name: obsolete retinal rod cell inner segment
description: The retinal rod cell region which contains the machinery of the cell (mitochondria, golgi, endoplasmic reticulum, etc) and where opsin molecules are assembled and passed to be part of the outer segment region

name: obsolete retinal rod cell outer segment
description: The retinal rod cell region which contains stacks of membranous discs separate from the outer cell membrane that are rich in the visual pigment rhodopsin

name: cortical intermediate zone
description: The region of the developing mammalian cortex that extends between the ventricular zone and the cortical plate (CP); normally, the IZ is a region of tangential migration of cells, and at midgestation, the lower part of the IZ develops into the subventricular zone

name: spleen primary B follicle
description: The nodules of small undifferentiated B lymphocytes and follicular dendritic cells located in the spleen white pulp

name: spleen secondary B follicle
description: The nodules of antigen-activated, differentiating B cells, follicular dendritic cells, antigen-presenting T cells and macrophages in the spleen white pulp
synonyms: ["secondary spleen B cell follicle","splenic secondary B cell follicle"]

name: semicircular canal ampulla
description: The spherical enlargement at the base of each semicircular canal where they connect with the utricle, containing the crista ampullaris which detects movement of the fluid within the canals

name: anterior visceral endoderm
description: The extraembryonic tissue that is responsible for the proper orientation of the anterior-posterior axis of the embryo and for appropriate patterning of adjacent embryonic tissue

name: tailgut
description: The extension of the hindgut of the primitive digestive tube of the embryo, caudal to the location of the anal opening

name: anterior definitive endoderm
description: The mesendoderm which first migrates from the node and which gives rise to the gut

name: basal cistern
description: The enclosed space where the arachnoid membrane stretches between the two temporal lobes and encloses the cerebral peduncles including the structures contained in the interpeduncular fossa

name: pontine cistern
description: The space located on lateral aspects of the pons at the junction with the celebellum

name: cerebellomedullary cistern
description: The largest of the subarachnoid cisterns between the cerebellum and the medulla oblongata; it is divided into a posterior cerebellomedullary cistern located between the cerebellum and the posterior surface of the medulla (also called cisterna magna), and a lateral cerebellomedullary cistern located between the cerebellum and the lateral aspect of the medulla.

name: subarachnoid cistern
description: The widening portions of the subarachnoid space within the cranium where the arachnoid bridges over a depression on the surface of the brain

name: lateral cerebellomedullary cistern
description: The space between the cerebellum and the lateral aspect of the medulla

name: quadrigeminal cistern
description: The enclosed space extending forward between the corpus callosum and the thalamus that contains the internal cerebral veins
synonyms: ["ambient cistern","cistern of great cerebral vein","cisterna ambiens","cisterna quadrigeminalis","cisterna venae magnae cerebri","superior cistern"]

name: external male genitalia
description: The external masculine genital organs, including the penis and scrotum

name: internal male genitalia
description: The internal masculine genital organs, including the testes, epididymides, deferent ducts, seminal vesicles, prostate, ejaculatory ducts, and bulbourethral glands

name: primitive pit
description: The small depression in the primitive streak that is caudal to the primitive node where the cells of the epiblast initially begin to invaginate during early embryogenesis

name: primitive groove
description: The shallow valley that extends along the length of the primitive streak

name: skeletal muscle fiber triad
description: The skeletal muscle fiber structure comprised of the transverse tubule and the two associated terminal cisternae; each fiber normally has thousands of triads

name: biliary ductule
description: One of the fine terminal elements of the bile duct system, leaving the portal canal, and pursuing a course at the periphery of a lobule of the liver. the excretory ducts of the liver that connect the interlobular ductules to the right or left hepatic duct

name: spinal cord medial motor column
description: The subclasses of motor neurons which project their axons to axial muscles that lie close to the vertebral column; motor neurons in the lateral subdivision of the MMC project their axons to body wall muscles

name: neural tube ventricular layer
description: The layer of undifferentiated, proliferating cells that line the neural tube lumen that is the immediate transformation of the germinal neuroepithelium
synonyms: ["ependymal layer","neural tube ependymal layer","neural tube ventricular germinal zone","neural tube ventricular zone"]

name: neural tube mantle layer
description: The layer of glia and differentiating neurons that forms as a second layer around the germinal neuroepithium; as this develops it comes to lie between the ventricular and marginal layers and includes the basal and alar plates. Develops into neurons and glia forming a gray matter layer.

name: neural tube marginal layer
description: The outermost layer of the neural tube that consists of axons from the developing mantle layer and will form the white matter

name: spinal cord alar plate
description: The region of the mantle layer of the neural tube that lies dorsal to the sulcus limitans and contains primarily sensory neurons and interneurons involved in communication of sensory impulses; the alar plate develops into the dorsal horn in the grey matter of the spinal cord
synonyms: ["alar column spinal cord","spinal cord alar column","spinal cord alar lamina"]

name: neural tube basal plate
description: The region of the mantle layer of the neural tube that lies ventral to the sulcus limitans and contains primarily motor neurons and interneurons.

name: frontonasal prominence
description: The unpaired embryonic prominence that is formed by the tissues surrounding the forebrain vesicle and develops into the forehead and bridge of the nose/snout.

name: lateral nasal prominence
description: The lateral area of the two branches of a horseshoe-shaped mesenchymal swelling in the future nasal region of the embryo; it separates the olfactory pit from the developing eye and the ala of the nose/snout develops from it

name: medial nasal prominence
description: The central area of the two limbs of a horseshoe-shaped mesenchymal swelling that lie medial to the olfactory placode or pit in the future nasal region of the embryo; it joins with the ipsilateral maxillary prominence in the formation of half of the upper jaw, and the nasal tip and philtrum of the upper lip develop from it

name: accessory olfactory bulb
description: The forebrain region that coordinates sensory signaling arising from the vomeronasal organ; it is located on the dorsal-posterior portion of the main olfactory bulb, and the axons that leave the accessory olfactory bulb project to targets in the amygdala and hypothalamus

name: cerebellum vermis lobule
description: The region of a cerebellar lobule that resides in the central section of the cerebellum between the two hemispheres.

name: cerebellum interpositus nucleus
description: The nucleus composed of the globose and emoliform nuclei of the cerebellum; in some mammalian species the globose nucleus is not distinguishable
synonyms: ["interposed nucleus of cerebellum","interposed nucleus of the cerebellum"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule I
synonyms: ["lingula (I)","lingula of anterior cerebellum vermis","lingula of cerebellum","lobule I of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis lingula","vermic lobule I"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule II
synonyms: ["central lobule","central lobule of cerebellum","lobule II","lobule II of cerebellum vermis","vermic lobule II"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule III
synonyms: ["central lobule","central lobule of cerebellum","lobule III","lobule III of cerebellum vermis","vermic lobule III"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule IV
synonyms: ["culmen of cerebellum","lobule IV of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis culmen","vermic lobule IV"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule IX
description: The uvula (uvular lobe) forms a considerable portion of the inferior vermis; it is separated on either side from the tonsil by the sulcus valleculC&, at the bottom of which it is connected to the tonsil by a ridge of gray matter, indented on its surface by shallow furrows, and hence called the furrowed band.
synonyms: ["cerebellar posterior vermis lobule IX","lobule IX of cerebellar posterior vermis","lobule IX of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis uvula","uvula (IX)","uvula [vermis]","uvula of cerebellum","uvula of vermis of cerebellum","vermic lobule IX"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule V
synonyms: ["culmen","culmen of cerebellum","lobule V","lobule V (culmen and quadrangular lobule, posterior part)","lobule V of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis culmen","vermic lobule V"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule VI
synonyms: ["declive","declive (VI)","declive lobule","declive of cerebellum","declive of vermis of cerebellum","lobule VI (declive and simplex lobule)","lobule VI of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis declive","vermic lobule vi"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule VII
synonyms: ["folium-tuber vermis (VII)","lobule VII of cerebellum vermis","vermic lobule VII"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule VIII
synonyms: ["cerebellum lobule VIII","lobule VIII of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis pyramis","neuraxis pyramus","pyramis","pyramis of vermis of cerebellum","pyramus","pyramus (VIII)","pyramus of cerebellum","pyramus of vermis of cerebellum","vermic lobule VIII"]

name: cerebellum vermis lobule X
synonyms: ["lobule X of cerebellum vermis","neuraxis nodule","neuraxis nodulus","nodule","nodulus","nodulus (X)","nodulus of cerebellum","nodulus of vermis of cerebellum","vermic lobule X"]

name: genital labium
description: One of the folds of skin which form the inner lips (labia minora) and outer lips (labia majora) on both sides of the vaginal opening.

name: labium majora
description: One of the folds of skin which form the outer lips on both sides of the vaginal opening

name: brain ventricle
description: one of the system of communicating cavities in the brain that are continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord, that like it are derived from the medullary canal of the embryo, that are lined with an epithelial ependyma, and that contain a serous fluid
synonyms: ["brain ventricles","cerebral ventricle","region of ventricular system of brain"]

name: vena cava
description: Any of the veins that carries deoxygenated blood from a part of the body into the right atrium of the heart.

name: orbital region
description: The subdivision of the face that includes the eye (eyeball plus adnexa such as eyelids) and the orbit of the skull and associated parts of the face such as the eyebrows, if present
synonyms: ["content of orbital part of eye","eye region","orbital part of face"]

name: midface
description: The middle of the face including the nose and its associated bony structures.

name: odontoid process of cervical vertebra 2
description: The toothlike process on the upper surface of the axis, which articulates with the atlas above.
synonyms: ["axis dens","axis odontoid process","cervical vertebra 2 odontoid process","dens","dens axis","dens of axis","odontoid process","odontoid process of axis"]

name: joint space of elbow
description: Joint cavity shared by all the joints of the elbow. The elbow joint is a compound joint that actually comprises three separate joints: the joints connecting the upper and lower arm: 1) Articulatio humero-ulnaris and 2) Articulatio humero-radialis as well as the proximal joint connecting the forarm bones: 3) Articulatio radio-ulnaris proximalis. All three share a joint cavity which is highly sinuated/scalloped/coved. Joint spaces of the elbow summarizes the joint cavity shared by all three adjoining joints of the elbow joint.

name: renal collecting system
description: The collecting duct system of the kidney consists of a series of tubules and ducts that connect the nephrons to the ureter. It participates in electrolyte and fluid balance through reabsorption and excretion, processes regulated by the hormones aldosterone and antidiuretic hormone.

name: alveolar ridge
description: one of the two jaw ridges either on the roof of the mouth between the upper teeth and the hard palate or on the bottom of the mouth behind the lower teeth. The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth.

name: hairline
description: Anatomical line demarcating the boundary between forehead and scalp.

name: subungual region
description: Region beneath a nail or claw.

name: crus of ear
description: horizontal piece of cartilage located outside the ear canal that divides the upper and lower parts of the ear.
synonyms: ["crus helicis","crus of helical part of auricular cartilage","crus of helix"]

name: clivus of occipital bone
description: Part of the cranium, the clivus is a shallow depression behind the dorsum sellC& that slopes obliquely backward. It forms a gradual sloping process at the anterior most portion of the basilar occipital bone at its junction with the sphenoid bone. On axial planes, it sits just posterior to the sphenoid sinuses. Just lateral to the clivus bilaterally is the foramen lacerum which contains the internal carotid artery, proximal to its anastamosis with the Circle of Willis. Posterior to the clivus is the basilar artery. The clivus supports the upper part of the pons.

name: cortex of humerus
description: The outer or sperficial part of the humerus.
synonyms: ["compact bone of humerus","cortex of the humerus","humerus compact bone","humerus cortical bone"]

name: midnasal cavity
description: An anatomical cavity that is the combination of the cavity between the nares and the choanae.

name: anatomical conduit
description: Any tube, opening or passage that connects two distinct anatomical spaces.

name: muscle of auditory ossicle
description: A muscle of the tympanic cavity that attaches to an auditory ossicle.
synonyms: ["auditory ossicles muscle","muscle of auditory ossicles","muscle of tympanic cavity","ossicular muscle","tympanic cavity muscle"]

name: tympanic cavity
description: small cavity surrounding the bones of the middle ear.
synonyms: ["anatomical cavity of middle ear","cavitas tympani","cavity of middle ear","middle ear cavity","middle-ear cavity"]

name: blood vessel of tympanic cavity
description: A blood vessel that is part of a tympanic cavity.
synonyms: ["anatomical cavity of middle ear blood vessel","blood vessel of anatomical cavity of middle ear","blood vessel of cavity of middle ear","blood vessel of middle ear anatomical cavity","blood vessel of middle ear cavity","cavity of middle ear blood vessel","middle ear anatomical cavity blood vessel","middle ear blood vessel","middle ear cavity blood vessel","tympanic cavity blood vessel"]

name: nerve of tympanic cavity
description: A nerve that is part of a tympanic cavity.
synonyms: ["anatomical cavity of middle ear nerve","cavity of middle ear nerve","middle ear anatomical cavity nerve","middle ear cavity nerve","nerve of anatomical cavity of middle ear","nerve of cavity of middle ear","nerve of middle ear anatomical cavity","nerve of middle ear cavity","tympanic cavity nerve","tympanic cavity nerves"]

name: pharyngeal pouch
description: An internal pocketing of pharyngeal endoderm that contacts a region of ectoderm (a pharyngeal cleft) and interdigitates in the anterior and posterior directions with the pharyngeal arches.

name: vasculature of iris
description: A vasculature that is part of a iris.
synonyms: ["iris blood vessels","iris vascular network","iris vasculature","vascular network of iris"]

name: endoderm-derived structure
description: An anatomical structure that develops (entirely or partially) from the endoderm.

name: mesoderm-derived structure
description: An anatomical structure that develops (entirely or partially) from the mesoderm.

name: ectoderm-derived structure
description: An anatomical structure that develops (entirely or partially) from the ectoderm.

name: genitourinary system
description: Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with the production and excretion of urine and those concerned with reproduction.

name: myocardial layer
description: Any of the layers of the myocardium. Example: compact layer, trabecular layer.

name: myocardium trabecular layer
description: The layer of the myocardium composed of projections of contractile myocytes. The trabecular layer is bounded internally by the endocardium. In zebrafish, unlike the trabeculations of higher vertebrates, both atrial and ventricular trabeculae have more strut-like character, and are more uniform without apparent regional differences.

name: myocardial compact layer
description: outer dense layer of the myocardium uniting the epicardium and myocardium.
synonyms: ["compact subepicardial layer","heart compact layer","myocardial compact layer","myocardium compact layer","subepicardial layer","subepicardium"]

name: trabecular layer of ventricle
description: A myocardium trabecular layer that is part of a cardiac ventricle.
synonyms: ["myocardium of region of ventricle","trabecular cardiac ventricle muscle","ventricular trabecular myocardium"]

name: compact layer of ventricle
description: The outer layer the ventricular myocardium, muscle fibers are arranged in a compact form and involved the entire ventricle.
synonyms: ["compact cardiac ventricle muscle","ventricle myocardium compact zone","ventricular compact myocardium","ventricular myocardial compact layer","ventricular myocardial compact zone"]

name: optic vesicle
description: The optic vesicle is the evagination of neurectoderm that precedes formation of the optic cup. Portion of tissue that is comprised of neuroepitheium which has pinched off from the anterior neural keel and will form the optic cup.

name: growth plate cartilage
description: cartilage that will provide a scaffold for mineralization of endochondral bones as they elongate or grow.

name: cerebellar layer
description: A cortical cell layer of the cerebellum. Examples: the granular (inner+outer) layer, molecular layer, Purkinje cell layer, and the ventricular layer of the embryo.
synonyms: ["cell layer of cerebellar cortex","cytoarchitectural part of the cerebellar cortex","gray matter layer of cerebellum","layer of cerebellar cortex","layer of cerebellum"]

name: trigeminal sensory nucleus
description: The sensory trigeminal nerve nuclei are the largest of the cranial nerve nuclei, and extend through the whole of the midbrain, pons and medulla. The nucleus is divided into three parts, from rostral to caudal (top to bottom in humans): * The mesencephalic nucleus * The chief sensory nucleus (or pontine nucleus or main sensory nucleus or primary nucleus) * The spinal trigeminal nucleus.
synonyms: ["sensory trigeminal nuclei","sensory trigeminal nucleus","sensory trigeminal V nucleus","trigeminal sensory nucleus","trigeminal V sensory nucleus"]

name: proximal tubule
description: In mammals, the proximal tubule is a nephron tubule that connects Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle. It has a brush border epithelial morphology.
synonyms: ["kidney proximal tubule","proximal kidney tubule","renal proximal tubule"]

name: distal tubule
description: The distal tubule is a nephron tubule that consists of the distal convoluted tubule and distal straight tubule segments

name: intermediate tubule
description: The intermediate tubule is a nephron tubule that lies between the proximal and distal tubules

name: somitomeric trunk muscle
description: The somitomeric trunk muscle is derived from somitomeric mesoderm. The muscle begins its development with the differentiation of the muscle cells and ends with the mature muscle. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus..

name: cardiogenic plate
description: The first recognizable structure derived from the heart field

name: primary heart field
description: A specific region of the lateral mesoderm that will form the primary beating heart tube. In mammals the primary heart field gives rise to the left ventricle.

name: heart tube
description: An epithelial tube that will give rise to the mature heart.

name: outflow tract septum
description: The outflow tract septum is a partition in the outflow tract

name: outflow tract
description: The outflow tract is the portion of the heart through which blood flows into the arteries

name: His-Purkinje system
description: The His-Purkinje system receives signals from the AV node and is composed of the fibers that regulate cardiac muscle contraction in the ventricles

name: cardiac vein
description: Vein of heart that drains the myocardium

name: ventriculo bulbo valve
description: A heart valve located between the ventricle and bulbus arteriosus.

name: coronary sinus valve
description: Vestigial cardiac valve which is continuous with the valve of the inferior vena cava.

name: cardiac chamber
description: A cardiac chamber surrounds an enclosed cavity within the heart

name: bulbus arteriosus
description: The bulbus arteriosus is an elastic heart chamber. Multi-tissue structure that consists of three layers and through which the blood exits the heart. The bulbus arteriosus is a pear shaped chamber that functions as a capacitor, maintaining continuous blood flow into the gill arches.

name: ventricular septum intermedium
description: Endocardial cushions project into the atrial canal, and, meeting in the middle line, unite to form the septum intermedium which divides the canal into two channels, the future right and left atrioventricular orifices.

name: atrial septum primum
description: In the developing heart, the cavity of the primitive atrium becomes subdivided into right and left chambers by a septum, the septum primum, which grows downward into the cavity. The increasingly smaller gap below it (before it fuses with the endocardial cushion) is known as the ostium primum. The septum primum eventually fuses with the endocardial cushion, closing the ostium primum off completely. Meanwhile, perforations appear in the superior part of the septum primum, forming the ostium secundum. This will eventually form part of the fossa ovalis.

name: proepicardium
description: An embryonic group of progenitor cells that forms from an outpouching of the septum transversum near the venous pole of the heart and gives rise to the epicardium

name: septum transversum
description: A thick plate of mesodermal tissue that occupies the space between the thoracic cavity and yolk stalk in the early embryo, forming a transverse partition partially separating the coelomic cavity into thoracic and abdominal portions. It gives rise to the central tendon of the diaphragm.

name: pulmonary myocardium
description: The pulmonary myocardium is the myocardial tissue present in the pulmonary vein

name: anterior ectodermal midgut
description: portions of the midgut that are derived from ectoderm.

name: branchiomeric muscle
description: A jaw muscle that arises from cranial mesenchyme and is innervated by cranial nerves.

name: orbitofrontal cortex
description: The region of the cerebral cortex covering the basal surface of the frontal lobes; this region normally controls emotion and decision making

name: spinal cord ventral commissure
description: The band of nerve fibers which cross the midline of the spinal cord ventral to the central canal and posterior grey commissure. The anterior (or ventral) white commissure, also known as the alba anterior medullae spinalis, is a bundle of nerve fibers which cross the midline of the spinal cord just anterior to the gray commissure. A N4 fibers and C fibers carrying pain sensation in the spinothalamic tract contribute to this commissure, as do fibers of the anterior corticospinal tract, which carry motor signals from the primary motor cortex.
synonyms: ["anterior white commissure","anterior white commissure of spinal cord","spinal cord anterior commissure","ventral spinal commissure","ventral white column","ventral white commissure of spinal cord"]

name: trigeminothalamic tract
description: The trigeminothalamic tract is one of the major routes of nociceptive and temperature signaling from the face

name: pons reticulospinal tract
description: Axon tract that carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body in the pons towards target cells in the spinal cord.

name: medulla reticulospinal tract
description: Axon tract that carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body in the medulla towards target cells in the spinal cord.

name: obsolete leg joint
description: Joint in the leg. For example the knee, which separates the leg tibia and femur

name: internal genitalia
description: The internal genitalia are the internal sex organs such as the uterine tube, the uterus and the vagina in female mammals, and the testis, seminal vesicle, ejaculatory duct and prostate in male mammals

name: external genitalia
description: The external genitalia are the outer sex organs, such as the penis or vulva in mammals

name: hemopoietic organ
description: Organ that is part of the hematopoietic system.
synonyms: ["haematological system organ","haemopoietic system organ","hematopoeitic organ","hematopoietic system organ","organ of haematological system","organ of haemopoietic system","organ of hematopoietic system","organ of organa haemopoietica","organa haemopoietica organ"]

name: aorta smooth muscle tissue
description: the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue located in the wall of the aorta
synonyms: ["aorta non-striated muscle","aorta smooth muscle","aortic smooth muscle"]

name: prostate glandular acinus
description: A saclike structure of the prostate gland, comprised of at least three cell layers: an innermost layer of secretory columnar luminal epithelium, a middle layer of squamous basal epithelium that also contains neuroendocrine cells, transit amplifying cells, and stem cells, and an outer layer of smooth muscle intermixed with other stromal cells

name: mammary gland fat
description: The mammary fat is an adipose structure in the gland that is invaded by the mammary ducts
synonyms: ["adipose tissue of lactiferous gland","adipose tissue of mammary gland","fat tissue of lactiferous gland","fat tissue of lobe of breast","fat tissue of lobe of mammary gland","fat tissue of mammary gland","fatty tissue of lactiferous gland","fatty tissue of lobe of breast","fatty tissue of lobe of mammary gland","fatty tissue of mammary gland","lactiferous gland adipose tissue","lactiferous gland fat tissue","lactiferous gland fatty tissue","lobe of breast adipose tissue","lobe of breast fat tissue","lobe of breast fatty tissue","lobe of mammary gland adipose tissue","lobe of mammary gland fat tissue","lobe of mammary gland fatty tissue","mammary gland adipose tissue","mammary gland fat tissue","mammary gland fatty tissue"]

name: mammary gland cord
description: The solid cord of epithelial cells that emerges from the mammary bud and grows down from the primary mammary mesenchyme and into a second stromal compartment, the fat pad precursor, beneath the dermis.

name: placental labyrinth blood vessel
description: The embryonic vessels grow through the layer to come in close contact with the maternal blood supply
synonyms: ["blood vessel of labyrinthine layer","blood vessel of labyrinthine layer of placenta","blood vessel of placenta labyrinth","labyrinthine layer blood vessel","labyrinthine layer of placenta blood vessel","placenta labyrinth blood vessel"]

name: prostate gland stroma
description: The prostate gland stroma is made up of the mesenchymal or fibroblast cells of the prostate gland
synonyms: ["prostate stroma","prostatic stroma","stroma of prostate","stroma of prostate gland"]

name: endodermal part of digestive tract
description: A portions of the gut that is derived from endoderm.

name: olfactory bulb mitral cell layer
description: The mitral cell layer is composed of pyramidal neurons whose cell bodies are located between the granule cell layer and the plexiform layer
synonyms: ["mitral cell body layer","mitral cell layer","OB mitral cell layer"]

name: Harderian gland
description: The Harderian gland is an anterior orbital gland usually associated with the nictitating membrane, and produces and secretes a variety of substances to the eye, depending upon the species.
synonyms: ["gland of Hardarian","glandula palpebra tertia profundus","Hardarian gland","Harder's gland"]

name: glomerular epithelium
description: The glomerular epithelium is an epithelial tissue that covers the outer surfaces of the glomerulus. The glomerular epithelium consists of both parietal and visceral epithelium. Metanephric glomerular parietal epithelial cells are specialized epithelial cells that form tight junctions as a barrier to protein transport. A metanephric glomerular visceral epithelial cell is a specialized epithelial cell that contains 'feet' that interdigitate with the 'feet' of other glomerular epithelial cells in the metanephros.
synonyms: ["epithelium of glomerulus","epithelium of kidney glomerulus","epithelium of renal glomerulus","kidney glomerular epithelium"]

name: glomerular endothelium
description: The glomerular endothelium is an epithelial tissue that covers the internal surfaces of the glomerulus

name: renal glomerulus vasculature
description: The glomerulus vasculature is composed of the tubule structures that carry blood or lymph in the glomerulus
synonyms: ["glomerulus vasculature","renal glomerulus vascular network","renal glomerulus vasculature","vascular network of renal glomerulus","vasculature of renal glomerulus"]

name: loop of Henle ascending limb thin segment
description: A sub-portion of the loop of Henle in the nephron of the kidney that is permeable to ions but not to water
synonyms: ["ascending limb thin segment of loop of Henle","ascending thin limb","pars ascendens (tubulus attenuatus)","thin ascending limb","thin ascending limb of loop of Henle"]

name: long nephron
description: Long nephrons are associated with juxtamedullary glomeruli and extend to the inner medulla

name: short nephron
description: Short nephrons are associated with mid-cortical glomeruli, and have no short ascending limb, so the limb is situated in the outer medulla

name: proximal convoluted tubule segment 1
description: The S1 portion is the initial portion of the proximal convoluted tubule and is responsible for avid reabsorption of water and solutes.
synonyms: ["proximal tubule segment 1","S1","S1 portion of renal tubule","S1 portion of tubule","segment 1 of proximal tubule"]

name: proximal convoluted tubule segment 2
description: The S2 portion of the tubule is involved in reabsorption of water and sodium chloride.
synonyms: ["proximal tubule segment 2","S2","S2 portion of renal tubule","S2 portion of tubule","segment 2 of proximal tubule"]

name: comma-shaped body
description: The comma-shaped body is the precursor structure to the S-shaped body that contributes to the morphogenesis of the nephron

name: S-shaped body
description: The S-shaped body is the successor of the comma-shaped body that contributes to the morphogenesis of the nephron

name: kidney pyramid
description: Kidney pyramids are the conical arrangements of tubules that constitute the renal medulla in a multi-lobed mammalian kidney; they contain the loops of Henle and the medullary collecting ducts.

name: kidney outer medulla inner stripe
description: The inner stripe is a deep, centrally located portion of the renal outer medulla and is traversed by thick and thin portions of nephron tubules
synonyms: ["inner stripe","inner stripe of medulla of kidney","inner stripe of outer medulla","inner stripe of renal medulla","outer medulla inner stripe","stria interna medullae renalis"]

name: kidney outer medulla outer stripe
description: The outer stripe is the region of the kidney that lies distal to the line of termination of the straight renal tubules
synonyms: ["outer medulla outer stripe","outer stripe","outer stripe of medulla of kidney","outer stripe of outer medulla","outer stripe of renal medulla","stria externa medullae renalis"]

name: cortical collecting duct
description: The cortical collecting duct is the portion of the collecting duct that resides in the renal cortex

name: outer medullary collecting duct
description: The outer medullary collecting duct is the portion of the collecting duct that lies in the renal outer medulla
synonyms: ["kidney outer medulla collecting duct","outer renal medulla collecting duct"]

name: inner medullary collecting duct
description: The inner medullary collecting duct is the portion of the collecting duct that lies in the renal inner medulla
synonyms: ["inner renal medulla collecting duct","kidney inner medulla collecting duct"]

name: long descending thin limb bend
description: The long descending thin limb bend is a part of the descending thin limb of a long nephron that lies beyond the prebend segment

name: prebend segment of loop of Henle
description: The prebend segment is a part of the descending thin limb that lies before the bend and exhibits robust sodium chloride reabsorption

name: nephrogenic mesenchyme
description: Nephrogenic mesenchyme is the tissue made up of loosely connected mesenchymal cells in the nephron

name: renal vesicle
description: The renal vesicle is the primordial structure of the nephron epithelium, and is formed by the condensation of mesenchymal cells.

name: nephron epithelium
description: The nephron epithelium is a tissue that covers the surface of a nephron
synonyms: ["epithelial tissue of nephron","epithelium of nephron","nephron epithelial tissue"]

name: glomerular capillary
description: the small branching blood vessels in the kidney glomerulus that receives blood from the kidney afferent arterioles; these capillaries are under high pressure for filtering within the glomerulus
synonyms: ["blood capillary of renal glomerulus","capillary of renal glomerulus","capillary vessel of renal glomerulus","renal glomerulus blood capillary","renal glomerulus capillary","renal glomerulus capillary vessel"]

name: vault of skull
description: Upper part of skull, consisting of parietals, frontals, post-parietals, and in some species the squamosal and a portion of the alisphenoid

name: allantois
description: A membranous sac that develops from the posterior part of the alimentary canal in the embryos of mammals, birds, and reptiles, and it is important in the formation of the umbilical cord and placenta in mammals.

name: primitive streak
description: The primitive streak is a structure that forms during the early stages of avian, reptilian and mammalian embryonic development. the midline ridge of the embryonic epiblast that later develops into mesoderm and endoderm

name: cardinal vein
description: Any of the four veins in the developing vertebrate embryo which run along each side of the vertebral column

name: trophectoderm
description: outermost layer of cells in the blastodermic vesicle, which will develop into the trophoblast layer and then contact the endometrium and take part in establishing the embryo's means of nutrition

name: gubernaculum (male or female)
description: embryonic structures which begin as undifferentiated mesenchyme attaching to the caudal end of the gonads. The gubernaculum is present only during the development of the urinary and reproductive organs, being replaced by distinct vestiges in males and females. Enitoinguinal ligaments that, in the male, connect the fetal testis to the developing scrotum, and, in the female, connect the ovaries to the uterus

name: limb bud
description: An outgrowth on the lateral trunk of the embryo that develops into a limb. The limb bud is divided into ectoderm and mesenchyme.

name: optic eminence
description: The embryonic structure that gives rise to the corneal ectoderm

name: female inguinal canal
description: An inguinal canal that is part of a female organism. Conveys the round ligament + the ilioinguinal nerve..

name: male inguinal canal
description: An inguinal canal that is part of a male organism. Conveys the spermatic cord and its coverings + the ilioinguinal nerve..

name: apical ectodermal ridge
description: multilayered ectodermal region at the distal tip of a limb or fin bud necessary for the proper development of the underlying mesenchyme. Along with the zone of polarizing activity, it is a crucial organizing region during limb development.

name: paired limb/fin bud
description: An outgrowth on the lateral trunk of the embryo that develops into a limb or paired fin. The limb/fin bud is divided into ectoderm and mesenchyme.
synonyms: ["limb - fin bud","paired appendage bud","paired limb/fin bud"]

name: caput epididymis
description: The head of the epididymis
synonyms: ["caput","epididymal head","epididymis head","epidymis head","head of epididymis","head of epidymis"]

name: corpus epididymis
description: The body of the epididymis
synonyms: ["body of epididymis","body of epidymis","epididymal body","epididymis body","epidymis body"]

name: cauda epididymis
description: The tail of the epididymis
synonyms: ["cauda epididymidis","corpus","epididymal cauda","epididymal tail","epididymis tail","epidymis tail","tail of epididymis","tail of epidymis"]

name: stylohyoid ligament
description: The fibrous cord that connects the tip of the styloid process of the temporal bone to the lesser horn of the hyoid bone

name: pharyngeal arch 1
description: The first of the series of pharyngeal arches that develop into jaw bones or their homologs, and their associated nerves and arteries
synonyms: ["1st pharyngeal arch","branchial arch 1","first branchial arch","first pharyngeal arch","first visceral arch","mandibular arch","visceral arch 1"]

name: pharyngeal arch artery
description: One of a series of paired embryological vascular structures formed within a pharyngeal arch; in the adult, some of these vessels give rise to the great vessels
synonyms: ["aortic arch","aortic arches","branchial aortic arches","branchial arch artery","embryonic aortic arch artery","PAA","pharyngeal arch artery"]

name: ectoplacental cone
description: thickened trophoblast of the blastocyst in rodents that becomes the fetal portion of the placenta

name: vitelline blood vessel
description: blood vessel that is connected to the yolk sac.

name: extraembryonic ectoderm
description: layer of the endoderm of the extraembryonic tissue.

name: Descemet's membrane
description: A transparent homogeneous acellular layer found between the substantia propria and the endothelial layer of the cornea.
synonyms: ["Descemet membrane","Descemet's posterior elastic lamina","lamina limitans posterior","lamina limitans posterior corneae","posterior limiting lamina","posterior limiting lamina of cornea","posterior limiting membrane"]

name: Reichert's cartilage
description: A continuous cartilaginous formation in mesenchyme of the second pharyngeal arch in the embryo. The longer cranial or styloid segment is continuous with the otic capsule; its inferior end is angulated and is situated very close to the oropharynx. The smaller caudal segment is in contact with the body and greater horn of the hyoid cartilaginous structure
synonyms: ["hyaloid cartilage","hyoid cartilage","Reichert cartilage","second branchial arch cartilage","second pharyngeal arch cartilage"]

name: Reichert's membrane
description: An nonvascular extraembryonic basement membrane that forms on the inner surface of the trophectoderm during placenta morphogenesis and is secreted by the distal parietal endoderm; required for the maternofetal exchange of nutrients and is important for the postgastrulation development. a thick multilayered basement membrane between the parietal endoderm cells and the trophoblast cells

name: anterior limiting lamina of cornea
description: A transparent homogeneous acellular layer, 6 to 9 um thick, lying between the basal lamina of the outer layer of stratified epithelium and the substantia propria of the cornea; it is considered to be a basement membrane.
synonyms: ["anterior elastic lamina","anterior limiting lamina","anterior limiting lamina of cornea","Bowman's anterior elastic lamina","Bowman's layer","Bowman's membrane","lamina limitans anterior (cornea)","lamina limitans anterior corneae"]

name: vitelline vasculature
description: vascular network that is connected to the yolk sac.

name: bone of free limb or fin
description: A bone that is part of an appendage.
synonyms: ["appendage bone","bone of appendage","bone of free segment of appendicular skeleton"]

name: fin bone
description: A bone that is part of a fin.

name: distal metaphysis

name: proximal metaphysis
description: A metaphysis that is in the proximal side of a diaphysis.

name: distal epiphysis

name: proximal epiphysis

name: venous system

The twelfth has angle nor costal groove; it is much shorter than the eleventh rib, and its head is inclined slightly downward. Sometimes the twelfth rib is even shorter than the first rib..

description: The third of the seven cervical vertebrae.
