description: On the lower surface of the basilar part of occipital bone, about 1 cm. in front of the foramen magnum, is the pharyngeal tubercle which gives attachment to the fibrous raphC) of the pharynx, also known as the pharyngeal raphe. This is the point of attachment for the superior pharyngeal constrictor muscle.

name: spinal vein
description: A vein that is part of a vertebral column.

name: median sacral vein
description: The median sacral vein (or middle sacral veins) accompany the corresponding artery along the front of the sacrum, and join to form a single vein, which ends in the left common iliac vein; sometimes in the angle of junction of the two iliac veins.

name: sublingual caruncle
description: The sublingual caruncle is a site on either side of the frenulum linguae on the sublingual surface of the tongue. There it denotes the site at which the submandibular gland empties into the oral cavity.

name: frenulum of tongue
description: A small fold of mucous membrane extending from the floor of the mouth to the midline of the underside of the tongue.
synonyms: ["frenulum","frenulum linguae","frenulum linguae","frenulum linguæ","frenulum of the tongue","lingual frenulum","tongue frenulum"]

name: deep dorsal vein of clitoris
description: The deep dorsal vein of clitoris is a vein which drains to the vesical plexus.

name: tentorium cerebelli
description: The tentorium cerebelli or cerebellar tentorium is an extension of the dura mater that separates the cerebellum from the inferior portion of the occipital lobes.

name: vertebral canal
description: A conduit enclosed within the vertebral foramen of the vertebrae through which the spinal cord passes.

name: cerebellum vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a cerebellum.

name: mammillary axonal complex
description: The mammillary axonal complex is formed by the axons from the lateral, medial mammillary and the dorsal premammillary nuclei which share a branching pattern. Every neuron gives off one axonal stem that bifurcates into 2 branches. One of the branches is directed dorsally to the thalamus and another caudally to the midbrain.

name: mammillothalamic axonal tract
description: A fiber pathway that originates from neurons in the posterior hypothalamic region and projects to various nuclei of the anterior nuclear group of the thalamus. It is a composite structure that consists of the mammillothalamic tract of the hypothalamus and the mammillothalamic tract of the thalamus (Carpenter-1983). (from Brain Info.org)

name: mammillotectal axonal tract
description: The mammillotectal tract is the collection of axons that connects the ventral diencephalon to the superior colliculus.

name: mammillotegmental axonal tract
description: The mammillotegmental tract is the collection of axons that connects the ventral diencephalon to the tegmentum and pons
synonyms: ["Gudden tract","mammillotegmental fasciculus","mammillotegmental tract","mammillotegmental tract of hypothalamus","MTG","von Gudden's tract"]

name: foramen cecum of tongue
description: The median pit on the dorsum of the posterior part of the tongue, from which the limbs of a V-shaped furrow run forward and outward; the foramen cecum is the point of attachment of the thyroglossal duct and is formed during the embryological descent of the thyroid gland
synonyms: ["blind foramen of tongue","cecal foramen of tongue","ductus lingualis","foramen caecum linguae","foramen cecum of tongue","foramen of Morgagni","Morand's foramen","Morgagni foramen"]

name: foramen cecum of frontal bone
description: The frontal crest of the frontal bone ends below in a small notch which is converted into a foramen, the foramen cecum, by articulation with the ethmoid. This foramen varies in size in different subjects, and is frequently impervious; when open, it transmits a vein from the nose to the superior sagittal sinus. This has clinical importance in that infections of the nose and nearby areas can be transmitted to the meninges and brain from what is known as the danger triangle of the face.

name: tibiofibula
description: Paired, endochondral bones formed by the fusion of the tibia and fibula. They form the shanks, extending from the knees to the ankles.

name: radio-ulna
description: Paired, long bones of endochondral origin formed by the fusion of the radius and ulna.

name: mesopodium region
description: The third segment of the limb, including either the wrist segment (carpus) or the ankle segment (tarsus)

name: autopodial skeleton
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in an autopodium region.
synonyms: ["autopod skeleton","autopodial skeleton","skeletal parts of autopod","skeleton of autopod"]

name: medial pterygoid muscle
description: The medial pterygoid is a pharyngeal arch 1 muscle that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors and is innervated by the nerve to the medial pterygoid and attaches to the cranial base and the medial side of the mandibular angle.
synonyms: ["musculus pterygoideus internus","musculus pterygoideus medialis","pterygoid medialis","pterygoideus medial","pterygoideus medialis"]

name: lateral pterygoid muscle
description: Pharyngeal arch 1 muscle that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors, is innervated by the lateral pterygoid nerve branches, and attaches to the condylar process of the mandible and temporomandibular joint (TMJ) capsule, and the cranial base.
synonyms: ["external pterygoid muscle","lateral pteregoid","lateral pteregoid muscle","lateral pterygoid","m. pterygoideus externus","m. pterygoideus lateralis","musculus pterygoides lateralis","musculus pterygoideus externus","musculus pterygoideus lateralis","pterygoid lateralis","pterygoideus externus","pterygoideus externus muscle","pterygoideus lateral","pterygoideus lateral muscle"]

name: alisphenoid bone
description: either of the broad curved wing like expanses on each side of the sphenoid bone in adults; may exist independently in the young
synonyms: ["ala major (os sphenoidale)","alisphenoid bone","greater wing of sphenoid","greater wing of sphenoidal bone"]

name: manubrium of malleus
description: The handle of the malleus; the portion that extends downward, inward, and backward from the neck of the malleus; it is embedded throughout its length in the tympanic membrane.

name: cochlear modiolus
description: the central cone shaped core of spongy bone about which turns the spiral canal

name: osseus spiral lamina
description: The osseous spiral lamina is a bony shelf or ledge which projects from the modiolus into the interior of the canal, and, like the canal, takes two-and-three-quarter turns around the modiolus. It reaches about half-way toward the outer wall of the tube, and partially divides its cavity into two passages or scalae, of which the upper is named the scala vestibuli, while the lower is termed the scala tympani.
synonyms: ["lamina modioli cochleae","lamina of modiolus cochleae","lamina of modiolus of cochlea","osseous spiral lamina","osseous spiral lamina of cochlea","spiral lamina of modiolus"]

name: spiral ligament
description: A spiral thickening of the fibrous lining of the cochlear wall. Spiral ligament secures the membranous cochlear duct to the bony spiral canal of the cochlea. Its spiral ligament fibrocytes function in conjunction with the stria vascularis to mediate cochlear ion homeostasis.
synonyms: ["ligamentum spirale ductus cochlearis","spiral cochlear ligament","spiral ligament of cochlea","spiral ligament of cochlear duct"]

name: outer canthus
description: A corner of the outer (lateral) part of an eye.

name: liver left lateral lobe
synonyms: ["lateral segment of left lobe of liver","lateral segment of liver","segmentum laterale (lobus hepatis sinister)"]

name: liver left medial lobe
synonyms: ["medial segment of left lobe of liver","medial segment of liver","segmentum mediale (lobus hepatis sinister)"]

name: liver perisinusoidal space
description: the extravascular space in the liver between the parenchymal cells and a sinusoid that contains the blood plasma
synonyms: ["Disse's space","hepatic perisinusoidal space","perisinusoidal space of Disse","space of Disse","spatium perisinusoideum"]

name: canthus
description: A canthus is a corner of the eye where the upper and lower eyelids meet. The bicanthal plane is the transversal plane linking both canthi and defines the upper boundary of the midface.

name: paleodentate of dentate nucleus
synonyms: ["paleodentate of dentate nucleus","paleodentate part of dentate nucleus","paleodentate portion of dentate nucleus","PDT"]

name: median lingual swelling
description: During the third week of embryological development there appears, immediately behind the ventral ends of the two halves of the mandibular arch, a rounded swelling named the tuberculum impar, which was described by His as undergoing enlargement to form the buccal part of the tongue. More recent researches, however, show that this part of the tongue is mainly, if not entirely, developed from a pair of lateral swellings which rise from the inner surface of the mandibular arch and meet in the middle line. The site of their meeting remains post-embryonically as the median sulcus of the tongue. The tuberculum impar is said to form the central part of the tongue immediately in front of the foramen cecum, but Hammar insists that it is purely a transitory structure and forms no part of the adult tongue.
synonyms: ["median lingual swelling","median tongue bud","tuberculum impar","tuberculum linguale mediale"]

name: lateral lingual swelling
description: During the third week there appears, immediately behind the ventral ends of the two halves of the mandibular arch, a rounded swelling named the tuberculum impar, which was described by His as undergoing enlargement to form the buccal part of the tongue. More recent researches, however, show that this part of the tongue is mainly, if not entirely, developed from a pair of lateral swellings (or distal tongue bud) which rise from the inner surface of the mandibular arch and meet in the middle line.

name: corneo-scleral junction
description: the edge of the cornea where it joins the sclera; the limbus is a common site for the occurrence of corneal epithelial neoplasm
synonyms: ["cornea limbus","corneal limbus","corneal limbus","corneal-scleral limbus","corneoscleral junction","limbus corneae","sclerocorneal junction","sclerocorneal limbus"]

name: suspensory ligament of lens
description: The zonule of Zinn (Zinn's membrane, ciliary zonule) is a ring of fibrous strands connecting the ciliary body with the crystalline lens of the eye. The zonule of Zinn is split into two layers: a thin layer, which lines the hyaloid fossa, and a thicker layer, which is a collection of zonular fibers. Together, the fibers are known as the suspensory ligament of the lens. Modified or toughened vitreous that suspend the lens at the equator to the non-pigmented epithelium of the ciliary zone. In zebrafish, dorsal zonules are thickened as compared to ventral zonules. In both dorsal and ventral regions, these fibers delimit the vitreous body aqueous humor boundary.

name: epithelium of conjunctiva
description: Layer of nonkeratinized squamous epithelium lining the conjunctiva, overlying scleral tissue

name: anterior communicating artery
description: A blood vessel of the brain that connects the left and right anterior cerebral arteries. The anterior communicating artery connects the two anterior cerebral arteries across the commencement of the longitudinal fissure. Sometimes this vessel is wanting, the two arteries joining together to form a single trunk, which afterward divides; or it may be wholly, or partially, divided into two. Its length averages about 4 mm, but varies greatly. It gives off some of the anteromedial ganglionic vessels, but these are principally derived from the anterior cerebral artery. It is part of the cerebral arterial circle, also known as the circle of Willis.

name: head of femur
description: The hemispheric articular surface at the upper extremity of the thigh bone. The femur head is the highest part of the thigh bone. It is supported by the neck of the femur. The head is globular and forms rather more than a hemisphere, is directed upward, medialward, and a little forward, the greater part of its convexity being above and in front. Its surface is smooth, coated with cartilage in the fresh state, except over an ovoid depression, the fovea capitis femoris, which is situated a little below and behind the center of the head, and gives attachment to the ligament of head of femur. If there is a fracture of the neck of the femur, the blood supply through the ligament becomes crucial. In orthopedic surgery, the head of the femur is important because it can undergo avascular necrosis and consequent osteochondritis dissecans. The head is removed in total hip replacement surgery.

name: long bone epiphyseal plate proliferative zone
description: germinal layer of the epiphyseal plate where cells are actively dividing as well as producing extracellular matrix.

name: long bone epiphyseal plate hypertrophic zone
description: The layer of the epiphyseal plate of a long bone where chondrocytes mature and enlarge.

name: long bone epiphyseal plate ossification zone
description: layer of the epiphyseal plate where new bone matrix is deposited.

name: annular epiphysis
description: secondary growth centers occurring as rings at the periphery of the superior and inferior surfaces of the vertebral body.

name: tectal plate
description: embryologic structure that is formed by two longitudinal eminences, one on each alar plate of the midbrain. These eminences become the superior colliculus and inferior colliculus ( Carpenter-1983 )]

name: superficial white layer of superior colliculus
description: superficial white matter layer of superior collilculus that consists mainly of axions from the optic nerve.
synonyms: ["lamina colliculi superioris iii","lamina III of superior colliculus","layer III of superior colliculus","optic layer","optic layer of superior colliculus","stratum opticum colliculi superioris"]

name: zonal layer of superior colliculus
description: A thin layer consisting of small myelinated axons together with marginal and horizontal cells.
synonyms: ["lamina colliculi superioris I","lamina I of superior colliculus","layer I of superior colliculus","stratum zonale colliculi superioris","stratum zonale of midbrain","stratum zonale of superior colliculus"]

name: stratum lemnisci of superior colliculus
description: Composite layer of the superior colliculus lying deep to the stratum opticum, that can be further subdivided into fiber and cell rich layers (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 2nd ed., 1981, pg 544)

name: layer of superior colliculus
description: The microstructure of the optic tectum / superior colliculus varies across species. As a general rule, there is always a clear distinction between superficial layers, which receive input primarily from the visual system and show primarily visual responses, and deeper layers, which receive many types of input and project to numerous motor-related brain areas. The distinction between these two zones is so clear and consistent that some anatomists have suggested that they should be considered separate brain structures. In mammals, neuroanatomists conventionally identify seven layers.
synonyms: ["cytoarchitectural part of superior colliculus","layer of optic tectum"]

name: gray matter layer of superior colliculus
description: A central nervous system gray matter layer that is part of a superior colliculus.

name: white matter of superior colliculus
description: A central nervous system white matter layer that is part of a superior colliculus.
synonyms: ["predominantly white regional part of superior colliculus","white matter layer of superior colliculus"]

name: middle white layer of superior colliculus
synonyms: ["intermediate white layer","intermediate white layer of superior colliculus","lamina colliculi superioris v","lamina V of superior colliculus","layer V of superior colliculus","stratum album intermediale of superior colliculus","stratum medullare intermedium colliculi superioris"]

name: middle gray layer of superior colliculus
synonyms: ["intermediate gray layer","intermediate grey layer of superior colliculus","lamina colliculi superioris iv","lamina IV of superior colliculus","layer IV of superior colliculus","stratum griseum intermediale","stratum griseum intermediale of superior colliculus","stratum griseum intermedium colliculi superioris","stratum griseum mediale"]

name: deep gray layer of superior colliculus
synonyms: ["deep grey layer of superior colliculus","lamina colliculi superioris vi","lamina VI of superior colliculus","layer VI of superior colliculus","stratum griseum profundum","stratum griseum profundum colliculi superioris","stratum griseum profundum of superior colliculus"]

name: deep white layer of superior colliculus
description: deep white matter layer of superior collilculus that consists entirely of fibers.
synonyms: ["lamina colliculi superioris vii","lamina VII of superior colliculus","layer VII of superior colliculus","stratum album profundum","stratum album profundum of superior colliculus","stratum medullare profundum colliculi superioris"]

name: superficial layer of superior colliculus
description: The outermost layer of the superior colliculus.

name: intermediate layer of superior colliculus
description: A layer of superior colliculus that lies between the superficial layer and the deep layer.

name: deep layer of superior colliculus
description: The innermost layer of the superior colliculus.

name: visual processing part of nervous system
arthropod optic lobe
description: A region of the adult brain that processes the visual information from the compound eyes.

name: cephalopod optic lobe
description: Large lobes of the brain associated with the eyes. In octopods and some squids the optic lobes may be separated from the rest of the brain by an optic stalk of varying length. In Octopus the optic lobes contain 92 million cells compared with only 42 million in the main central mass of the brain (J. Young, 1963) .

name: efferent nerve
description: A nerve that transmits nerve impulses from the central nervous system to effectors such as muscles or glands.

name: glandular epithelium
description: An epithelium that is composed primarily of secretory cells.

name: anatomical line
description: Non-material anatomical entity of one dimension, which forms a boundary of an anatomical surface or is a modulation of an anatomical surface.

name: proximal head of humerus
description: Hemispherical structure on proximal epiphysis of humerus that articulates with glenoid cavity.

name: acetabular rim
description: A prominent unever rim that bounds the acetabulum, serving as the attachment for the acetabular labrum, which reduces its opening, and deepens the surface for formation of the hip joint.

name: obturator foramen
description: The obturator foramen is the hole created by the ischium and pubis bones of the pelvis through which nerves and muscles pass.

name: reticular tissue
description: Loose connective tissue which consists of an irregular network of cells and reticular fibers and is spatially associated with myeloid and lymphoid cells. Examples: stroma of bone marrow, stroma of spleen, stroma of lymph node.

name: sternal end of clavicle
description: Medial end of the clavicle, which usually lies on the ventral side of the epicoracoid cartilage, just posterior to the epicoracoid bridge.
synonyms: ["extremitas sternalis (clavicula)","extremitas sternalis claviculae","medial end of clavicle"]

name: entepicondyle of humerus
description: A bony projection on the distal epiphysis of the humerus that is the attachment site for the flexor muscles of the manus. This condyle faces posteriorly (for sprawling tetrapods) or medially (for erect tetrapods).

name: ectepicondyle of humerus
description: A bony projection on the distal epiphysis of the humerus that is the attachment site for the extensor muscles of the distal parts of the forelimb. In humans, this is known as the lateral epicondyle, but the position varies across tetrapods.

name: olecranon
description: The olecranon is a large, thick, curved bony eminence of the forearm that projects behind the elbow. It is situated at the upper (proximal) end of the ulna, one of the two bones in the forearm. When the hand faces forward the olecranon faces towards the back (posteriorly). It is bent forward at the summit so as to present a prominent lip which is received into the olecranon fossa of the humerus in extension of the forearm. Its base is contracted where it joins the body and the narrowest part of the upper end of the ulna. Its posterior surface, directed backward, is triangular, smooth, subcutaneous, and covered by a bursa. Its superior surface is of quadrilateral form, marked behind by a rough impression for the insertion of the Triceps brachii; and in front, near the margin, by a slight transverse groove for the attachment of part of the posterior ligament of the elbow-joint. Its anterior surface is smooth, concave, and forms the upper part of the semilunar notch. Its borders present continuations of the groove on the margin of the superior surface; they serve for the attachment of ligaments, viz. , the back part of the ulnar collateral ligament medially, and the posterior ligament laterally. From the medial border a part of the Flexor carpi ulnaris arises; while to the lateral border the anconeus muscle is attached.

name: occipital condyle
description: The occipital condyles are undersurface facets of the occipital bone in vertebrates, which function in articulation with the superior facets of the atlas vertebra. The condyles are oval or reniform (kidney-shaped) in shape, and their anterior extremities, directed forward and medialward, are closer together than their posterior, and encroach on the basilar portion of the bone; the posterior extremities extend back to the level of the middle of the foramen magnum. The articular surfaces of the condyles are convex from before backward and from side to side, and look downward and lateralward. To their margins are attached the capsules of the atlantoC6ccipital articulations, and on the medial side of each is a rough impression or tubercle for the alar ligament. At the base of either condyle the bone is tunnelled by a short canal, the hypoglossal canal.

name: mental foramen
description: The mental foramen is one of two holes ('foramina') located on the anterior surface of the mandible. It permits passage of the mental nerve and vessels. The mental foramen descends slightly in edentulous individuals.

name: nasal skeleton
description: Structural framework that provides support to the nasal sacs and ducts.

name: areolar connective tissue
description: Loose connective tissue located at the outer and inner layers of organs. Examples: submucosal connective tissue, tunica adventitia of artery, papillary dermis, superficial fascia of dorsum of hand.

name: body of sternum
description: The middle and longest portion of the sternum, lying between the manubrium superiorly and the xiphoid process inferiorly; it considerably lengthier, narrower, and thinner than the manubrium, attains its greatest breadth close to the lower end.

name: proximal epiphysis of ulna
description: The head of ulna presents an articular surface, part of which, of an oval or semilunar form, is directed downward, and articulates with the upper surface of the triangular articular disk which separates it from the wrist-joint; the remaining portion, directed lateralward, is narrow, convex, and received into the ulnar notch of the radius.
synonyms: ["caput ulnae","head of ulna","proximal end of ulna","upper end of ulna"]

name: trabecula carnea of atrium
description: The supporting bundles of muscular fibers lining the walls of the atria.

name: remnant of left anterior vena cava
lumen of open tracheal system trachea
description: An anatomical space that surrounded_by a open tracheal system trachea.

name: lumen of trachea
description: An anatomical space that surrounded_by a trachea.

name: uterus or analog
description: A subdivision of a the reproductive tract in a female organism that is the site of embryo development.

name: obsolete arthropod oviduct
description: A tube that connects ovary to the uterus.

name: medial tibial tarsal bone
description: Endochondral tarsal bone that is medially located and between the intermedium and centralia.

name: tegmen tympani
description: The Tegmental Wall or Roof (paries tegmentalis) is formed by a thin plate of bone, the tegmen tympani, which separates the cranial and tympanic cavities. It is situated on the anterior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone close to its angle of junction with the squama temporalis; it is prolonged backward so as to roof in the tympanic antrum, and forward to cover in the semicanal for the Tensor tympani muscle. Its lateral edge corresponds with the remains of the petrosquamous suture .
synonyms: ["paries tegmentalis cavi tympani","tegmental roof of tympanic cavity","tegmental wall of tympanic cavity"]

name: ventral ramus of spinal nerve
description: Branch of spinal nerve that innervates the hypaxial muscles
synonyms: ["anterior primary ramus of spinal nerve","anterior ramus of spinal nerve","ramus anterior","ventral ramus","ventral ramus of spinal nerve"]

name: dorsal ramus of spinal nerve
description: Branch of spinal nerve that innervates the epaxial muscles
synonyms: ["dorsal ramus","posterior primary ramus","posterior ramus of spinal nerve","ramus posterior","ramus posterior nervi spinalis"]

name: nucleus of lateral lemniscus
description: Groups of cells situated largely within the fiber bundles of the lateral lemniscus. Two nuclei are usually distinguished: a ventral group and a dorsal group (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 3rd ed., 1981, pg. 619).
synonyms: ["lateral lemniscus nuclei","lateral lemniscus nucleus","nuclei lemnisci lateralis"]

name: central vein of liver
description: Vein that is central to a lobule in the liver.
synonyms: ["central vein","terminal branch of hepatic vein","terminal hepatic venule","vena centralis (hepar)"]

name: lymphatic capillary
description: Microvessel of the lymphatic system lined with a single layer of overlapping endothelial cells. Joins to form the lymphatic vessels.

name: root of cranial nerve
description: The initial segment of a cranial nerve, leaving the central nervous system.

name: cusp of tooth
description: A raised area of the biting surface of a tooth.

name: abductor muscle
description: A muscle that moves a body part away from the sagittal plane/midline of the body. For example, the abductor muscles of the legs spread the legs away from the midline and away from one another. An abductor muscle opposes an adductor muscle.

name: surface groove
description: A furrow or an incomplete tube.

name: cerebellar commissure
description: A nervous system commissure that connects a left hemisphere of cerebellum and connects a right hemisphere of cerebellum.

name: scapula
description: Endochondral bone that is dorsoventrally compressed and provides attachment site for muscles of the pectoral appendage.

name: renal cortex peritubular capillary
description: A peritubular capillary that is part of a cortex of kidney.

name: renal cortex tubule
description: A region of nephron tubule that is part of a cortex of kidney.

name: distal straight tubule postmacula segment
synonyms: ["cortical thick ascending limb of Henle's loop","kidney cortex loop of Henle ascending limb thick segment","renal cortex loop of Henle ascending limb thick segment","renal cortex thick ascending limb"]

name: muscular coat of ureter
description: A muscular coat that is part of a ureter.
synonyms: ["muscular coat of ureter","muscular layer of ureter","muscularis of ureter","tunica muscularis (ureter)","tunica muscularis ureteris"]

name: interrenal gland
description: Structures in fishes homologous to the cortical tissue of the mammalian adrenal gland; they are in close proximity to or imbedded in the head kidney.

name: adrenal/interrenal gland
description: This gland can either be a discrete structure located bilaterally above each kidney, or a cluster of cells in the head kidney that perform the functions of the adrenal gland. In either case, this organ consists of two cells types, aminergic chromaffin cells and steroidogenic cortical cells

name: swim bladder bud
description: Embryonic structure that forms from the anterior gut epithelium at the level of the second somite that then matures to form the swim bladder.

name: swim bladder
description: A thin membranous, sometimes alveolated sac in the dorsal portion of the abdominal cavity. Contains a varying mixture of gases, not identical to the composition of air. May be one, two or three chambered. May be connected to the gut by a tube, the ductus pneumaticus (then called physostomous) or unconnected (then called physoclistous).

name: diaphysis proper
description: Subdivision of long bone which forms the part of the bone between two metaphyses. Note that the diaphysis includes the metaphyses, but the diaphysis proper excludes these.
synonyms: ["body proper of long bone","shaft proper of long bone"]

name: diaphysis of femur
description: A diaphysis that is part of a femur.
synonyms: ["body of femur","corpus femoris","femoral diaphysis","femoral shaft","shaft of femur"]

name: proximal metaphysis of femur
description: A proximal metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: distal metaphysis of femur
description: A distal metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: metaphysis of femur
description: A metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: terminal part of digestive tract
description: The distalmost portion of the digestive tract, derived from the hindgut, and terminating with the anus.

name: anal part of perineum
description: The anal triangle is the posterior part of the perineum. It contains the anal canal..

name: seminal fluid secreting gland
description: A gland that secretes a seminal fluid.

name: electric organ
description: A specialized tract of tissue (as in the electric eel) in which electricity is generated.

name: endostyle
description: An endostyle is a longitudinal ciliated groove on the ventral wall of the pharynx which produces mucus to gather food particles. It is found in urochordates and cephalochordates, and in the larvae of lampreys. It aids in transporting food to the esophagus. It is also called the hypopharyngeal groove. The endostyle in larval lampreys (ammocetes) metamorphoses into the thyroid gland in adults, and is regarded as being homologous to the thyroid gland in vertebrates. However, Dumont, et al. question whether the endostyle in ammocetes is homologous with that of the urochordates and cephalochordates. Since the endostyle is found in the three branches of chordates, it is presumed to have arisen in the common ancestor of these taxa, along with a shift to internal feeding for extracting suspended food from the water.

name: embryonic footplate
description: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the pes (foot)

name: handplate apical ectodermal ridge
description: An apical ectodermal ridge that is part of a handplate.

name: embryonic handplate
description: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the manus (hand)

name: vasculature of organ
description: A vasculature that is part of a organ.
synonyms: ["organ vasculature","set of blood vessels of organ"]

name: vasculature of liver
description: A vasculature that is part of a liver.

name: decidua parietalis
description: The part of the decidua in the pregnant human female lining the uterus.

name: head mesenchyme from mesoderm
description: A head mesenchyme that develops_from a mesoderm.
synonyms: ["head mesenchyme derived from mesoderm","head mesenchyme from head mesoderm","head mesenchyme from mesoderm","mesenchyme derived from head mesoderm","mesenchyme from head mesoderm"]

name: mandibular process mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a mandibular prominence.
synonyms: ["mesenchyme of mandibular process","mesenchyme of mandibular prominence"]

name: ala of nose
description: The lateral surface parts of the external nose, inferiorly, surrounding the naris.

name: slow muscle tissue
description: The darker-colored muscle tissue of some mammals, composed of slow twitch muscle fibers.
synonyms: ["slow muscle","slow skeletal muscle tissue","slow-twitch skeletal muscle"]

name: fast muscle tissue
description: The paler-colored muscle tissue of some mammals, composed of fast twitch muscle fibers.

name: lumen of digestive tract
description: An anatomical space that surrounded_by a digestive tract.
synonyms: ["digestive tract lumen","gut cavity","gut lumen","lumen of alimentary tract","lumen of digestive tract","lumen of gut"]

name: urinary bladder muscularis mucosa
description: A thin layer of smooth muscle within the bladder lamina propria.
synonyms: ["muscularis mucosa of bladder","muscularis mucosa of urinary bladder"]

name: lip epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a lip.

name: squamous epithelium
description: An epithelium characterised by its most superficial layer consisting of squamous epithelial cells.

name: stratified squamous epithelium
description: Multilaminar epithelium which consists of more than one layer of squamous cells only one layer of which is in contact with a basement membrane. Examples: keratinized stratified squamous epithelium, epithelium of wall of esophagus.

name: non-keratinized epithelium of tongue
description: A non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium that is part of a tongue.

name: parakeratinized epithelium of tongue
description: A parakeratinized epithelium that is part of a tongue.

name: tongue squamous epithelium
description: A squamous epithelium that is part of a tongue.

name: esophagus squamous epithelium
description: A squamous epithelium that is part of a esophagus.

name: stomach squamous epithelium
description: A squamous epithelium that is part of a stomach.

name: cervix squamous epithelium
description: The squamous epithelium of the cervical portio is similar to that of the vagina, except that it is generally smooth and lacks rete pegs. Colposcopically, it appears featureless except for a fine network of vessels which is sometimes visible. The relative opacity and pale pink coloration of the squamous epithelium derives from its multi-layered histology and the location of its supporting vessels below the basement membrane.

name: vagina squamous epithelium
description: A squamous epithelium that is part of a vagina.

name: stomach glandular epithelium
description: A glandular epithelium that lines the stomach. The stomach's glandular epithelium is characterized by the presence of gastric glands.

name: digestive system gland
description: Any gland that is part of the digestive system.

name: glandular columnar epithelium
description: Simple columnar epithelium that constitutes the secretory part of a gland. Examples: epithelium of stomach, luminal epithelium of lactiferous duct.

name: stomach glandular region mucosa
description: stomach mucosa that is lined with glandular epithelium and part of a stomach glandular region.

name: vestibular epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a vestibular labyrinth.
synonyms: ["epithelium of vestibular labyrinth","inner ear vestibular component epithelium","vestibular sensory epithelium"]

name: sensory epithelium
description: Simple columnar epithelium made up of cells specialized to serve as sensory cells for the reception of external stimuli, as the sensory cells of the cochlea, vestibule, nasal mucosa, and tongue.

name: crista ampullaris neuroepithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a crista ampullaris.
synonyms: ["epithelium of crista of ampulla of semicircular duct of membranous labyrinth"]

name: thymus subcapsular epithelium
description: the epithelial cells lining the capsule and trabeculae of the thymus

name: inner ear epithelium
description: the epithelial cell layer containing the sensory hair cells and their associated sensory nerve terminals

name: pinna surface epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a pinna.

name: efferent duct
description: The efferent ducts (or efferent ductules or ductuli efferentes) connect the rete testis with the initial section of the epididymis. The ductuli are unilaminar and composed of columnar ciliated and non-ciliated (absorptive) cells. The ciliated cells serve to stir the luminal fluids, possibly to help ensure homogeneous absorption of water from the fluid produced by the testis, which results in an increase in the concentration of luminal sperm. The epithelium is surrounded by a band of smooth muscle that helps to propel the sperm toward the epididymis.

name: male genital duct
description: A duct or series of ducts that transports sperm from the gonad. In mammals this is from the seminiferous tubules through rete testis, vas efferentia, epididymis, vas deferens, ejeculatory duct to the urethra.

name: efferent duct epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a efferent duct.

name: cervical loop
description: The cervical loop is the location on an enamel organ in a developing tooth where the outer enamel epithelium and the inner enamel epithelium join. The cervical loop is a histologic term indicating a specific epithelial structure at the apical side of the tooth germ, consisting of loosely aggregated stellate reticulum in the center surrounded by stratum intermedium. These tissues are enveloped by a basal layer of epithelium known on the outside of the tooth as outer enamel epithelium and on the inside as inner enamel epithelium. During root formation the inner layers of epithelium disappear and only the basal layers are left creating Hertwig's Epithelial Root Sheath (HERS). At this point it is usually referred to as HERS instead of the cervical loop to indicate the structural difference.

name: stellate reticulum
description: The stellate reticulum is a group of cells located in the center of the enamel organ of a developing tooth. These cells are star shaped and synthesize glycosaminoglycans. As glycosamingoglycans are produced, water is drawn in between the cells and stretch them apart. As they are moved further away from one another, the stellate reticulum maintain contact with one another through desmosomes, resulting in their unique appearance. stellate reticulum is lost after the first layer of dentin is laid down. this brings cells in inner enamel epithelium closer to blood vessels at the periphery.

name: inner dental epithelium
description: Inner layer of cells of the dental organ, nearest the odontogenic papilla, and composed of ameloblasts.

name: outer dental epithelium
description: Outer layer of cells of the dental organ.
synonyms: ["external dental epithelium","external enamel epithelium","outer enamel epithelium"]

name: ejaculatory duct epithelium
description: The ejaculatory duct epithelium is composed of cuboidal to columnar cells between or through which project the terminal parts of the ducts of the unicellular prostate glands.

name: mammary gland myoepithelium
description: the outer cell layer of the mammary gland epithelium bilayer which is located basal to the luminal (secretory) cells and adjacent to the basement membrane.
synonyms: ["lactiferous ductal myo-epithelium","mammary myoepithelium","myo-epithelium of lactiferous duct","myoepithelium of lactiferous duct"]

name: uterine epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a uterus.

name: buccal mucosa
description: The inner lining of the cheeks and lips.

name: submandibular gland primordium epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a submandibular gland primordium.

name: great vein of heart
description: The Great Cardiac Vein (left coronary vein) begins at the apex of the heart and ascends along the anterior longitudinal sulcus to the base of the ventricles. It then curves to the left in the coronary sulcus, and reaching the back of the heart, opens into the left extremity of the coronary sinus. It receives tributaries from the left atrium and from both ventricles: one, the left marginal vein, is of considerable size, and ascends along the left margin of the heart.

name: mandible angular process
description: A process which protrudes from the ventral caudal angle of the mandible, and acts as the attachment of the digastric muscle.

name: ovary stroma
description: The stroma of the ovary is a peculiar soft tissue, abundantly supplied with blood vessels, consisting for the most part of spindle-shaped cells with a small amount of ordinary connective tissue. These cells have been regarded by some anatomists as unstriped muscle cells, which, indeed, they most resemble; by others as connective-tissue cells. On the surface of the organ this tissue is much condensed, and forms a layer composed of short connective-tissue fibers, with fusiform cells between them. The stroma of the ovary may contain interstitial cells resembling those of the testis.
synonyms: ["interstitial tissue of ovary","ovarian stroma","ovary stroma","stroma of the ovary","stroma ovarica"]

name: pars distalis of adenohypophysis
description: The distal part of adenohypophysis: the part that makes up the main body of the gland.
synonyms: ["DHP","distal part of hypophysis","pars anterior","pars anterior of adenohypophysis","pars distalis (glandula pituitaria)","pars distalis adenohypophysis","pars distalis of anterior lobe of pituitary gland","pars glandularis of adenohypophysis"]

name: vascular cord
description: The vascular cord is the primordial vasculature that will develop into blood vessels by the process of tubulogenesis. The vascular cord is composed of angioblast or vascular endothelial cells in a solid linear mass called a cord. The cord then undergoes tubulogenesis to form the lumen of the vessels.

name: coronary capillary
description: A capillary that is part of the coronary system.

name: horn
description: A pointed projection of the skin on the head of various animals, consisting of a covering of horn (keratin and other proteins) surrounding a core of living bone.

name: cranial appendage
description: An anatomical projection that is part of and protrudes from the head

name: antler
description: Antlers are the usually large, branching bony appendages on the heads of most deer species.

name: nephridium
description: An exceretory tubule that usually opens to the exterior by a nephridiopore. The inner end of the tubule may be blind, ending in flame cells (protonephridium) or may open into the coelom through a ciliated funnel (metanephridium).

name: protonephridium
description: A network of dead-end tubules lacking internal openings found in the Phylums Platyhelminthes, kinorhyncha and Rotifera.

name: metanephridium
description: A type of excretory gland or nephridium found in many types of invertebrates such as Annelids, Arthropods and Molluscs. It typically consists of a ciliated funnel opening into the body cavity or coelom connected to a duct which may be variously glandularized, folded or expanded (vesiculate) and which typically opens to the organism's exterior. These ciliated tubules pump water carrying surplus ions, metabolic waste, toxins from food, and useless hormones out of the organism through openings known as nephrostomes. This waste is passed out of the body at the nephridiopore. The primary urine produced by filtration of blood (or a similar functioning fluid) is modified into secondary urine through selective reabsorption by the cells lining the metanephridium. In many earthworms the nephridial ducts open into the digestive tract instead, a condition known as enteronephry.

name: peptonephridium
description: Organs opening into the buccal cavity of pharynx (supposedly modified nephridia) of invertebrates.

name: anatomical point
description: Non-material anatomical entity of zero dimension, which forms a boundary of an anatomical line or surface.

name: anatomical surface
description: A two dimensional anatomical structure that is the boundary between an anatomical structure and an anatomical substance, an anatomical space or the organism's environment. Examples include the surface of your skin, the surface of the lining of your gut; the surface of the endothelium of you aorta that is in contact with blood.n

name: cardiogenic splanchnic mesoderm
description: The splanchnic mesoderm in the cardiogenic region where the heart develops; it gives rise to endocardial heart tubes that fuse to form the primordial cardiac tube, the heart primordium. Two migratory heart primordia that move ventrally during the course of neurulation, and then fuse.

name: obsolete blastomere
description: A type of cell produced by division of the egg after fertilization.

name: cleaving embryo
description: Organism at the cleavage stage.

name: sexually immature organism
description: A multicellular organism that is at the juvenile stage.

name: adult organism
description: A multicellular organism that existence_ends_with a post-juvenile adult stage and existence_starts_with a post-juvenile adult stage.

name: presumptive gut
synonyms: ["future digestive tract","future digestive tube","future gut","primitive gut"]

name: chordo neural hinge
description: Portion of tissue that is posterior to the developing notochord during tail bud extension.

name: mandibular neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the mandibular arch.

name: hyoid neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the hyoid arch.

name: primary circulatory organ
description: A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood or analogs.

name: vitelline duct
description: A long narrow tube that joins the yolk-sac to the midgut lumen of the developing fetus.

name: chorionic villus
description: One of the minute vascular projections of the fetal chorion that combines with maternal uterine tissue to form the placenta.

name: vernix caseosa
description: An unctuous substance composed of sebum and desquamated epithelial cells, which covers the skin of the fetus.

name: meconium
description: A dark greenish mass that accumulates in the bowel during fetal life and is discharged shortly after birth.

name: Douglas' pouch
description: The rectouterine pouch (or rectouterine excavation, rectovaginal, Ehrhardt-Cole Recess or Pouch of Douglas) is the extension of the peritoneal cavity between the rectum and back wall of the uterus in the female human body. The rectouterine pouch is used in the treatment of end-stage renal failure in patients who are treated by peritoneal dialysis. The tip of the dialysis catheter is placed into the deepest point of the pouch. In women it is the deepest point of the peritoneal cavity, posterior to (behind) the uterus and anterior to (in front of) rectum. (The pouch on the other side of the uterus is the vesicouterine excavation. ) It is near the posterior fornix of the vagina. In men, the region corresponding to the rectouterine pouch is the rectovesical excavation, which lies between the urinary bladder and rectum. (There is no equivalent to the vesicouterine excavation.)
synonyms: ["excavatio recto-uterina","excavatio rectouterina","pouch of douglas","recto-uterine pouch","rectouterine pouch"]

name: venom
description: Poisonous animal secretions forming fluid mixtures of many different enzymes, toxins, and other substances. These substances are produced in specialized glands and secreted through specialized delivery systems (nematocysts, spines, fangs, etc.) for disabling prey or predator.

name: deciduous tooth
description: One of the first set of teeth in the growth development of humans and many other mammals.

name: primary dentition
description: The set of teeth first in order or time of development that will be replaced by permanent dentition upon their loss.
synonyms: ["baby teeth","deciduous teeth","dentes decidui","milk teeth","primary teeth","primary teeth","set of deciduous teeth","set of primary teeth","tooth of primary dentition"]

name: umbilicus
description: The pit in the center of the abdominal wall marking the point where the umbilical cord entered in the fetus.

name: neck of femur
description: The femur neck or neck of the femur is a flattened pyramidal process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft, and forming with the latter a wide angle opening medialward.

name: premolar tooth
description: The premolar teeth or bicuspids are transitional teeth located between the canine and molar teeth.

name: skin nerve field
description: A zone of skin that is mainly innervated by a single sensory nerve. A nerve field innervated by exactly one dorsal root is called a dermatome.

name: pharyngeal pouch 1
description: A pharyngeal pouch that is between pharyngeal arches 1 and 2.
synonyms: ["1st arch branchial pouch","1st arch branchial pouch endoderm","1st arch pouch endoderm","1st branchial pouch","1st pharyngeal pouch endoderm","first arch pharyngeal pouch","first visceral pouch","hyomandibular pouch","pharyngeal pouches 1","visceral pouch 1"]

name: pharyngeal pouch 2
description: A pharyngeal puch that is between the pharyngeal arches 2 and 3.
synonyms: ["2nd arch branchial pouch","2nd arch branchial pouch endoderm","2nd arch pouch endoderm","2nd branchial pouch","2nd pharyngeal pouch endoderm","pharyngeal pouches 2","second arch pharyngeal pouch","second visceral pouch","visceral pouch 2"]

name: pharyngeal pouch 3
description: A pharyngeal pouch that between pharyngeal arches 3 and 4.
synonyms: ["3rd arch branchial pouch","3rd arch branchial pouch endoderm","3rd branchial pouch","3rd pharyngeal pouch endoderm","pharyngeal pouches 3","third arch pharyngeal pouch","third visceral pouch","visceral pouch 3"]

name: pharyngeal pouch 4
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arch 4 and arch 5 or 6 (a fifth arch never establishes in amniotes).
synonyms: ["4th arch branchial pouch","4th arch branchial pouch endoderm","4th branchial pouch","4th pharyngeal pouch endoderm","fourth arch pharyngeal pouch","fourth branchial pouch","fourth visceral pouch","pharyngeal pouches 4","visceral pouch 4"]

name: pharyngeal pouch 5
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arches 5 and 6.
synonyms: ["5th branchial pouch","fifth visceral pouch","pharyngeal pouches 5","visceral pouch 5"]

name: pharyngeal pouch 6
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arches 6 and 7.
synonyms: ["6th arch branchial pouch","6th branchial pouch","pharyngeal pouches 6","sixth visceral pouch","visceral pouch 6"]

name: glomeral mesenchyme
description: Portion of tissue that consists of the precursors of the pronephric glomus or glomerulus; derived from the medial portion of the pronephric intermediate mesoderm.

name: head kidney
description: Teleost head kidney consists of fused bilateral lobes located in the anterior part of the kidney. It is analogous to the mammalian bone marrow and the primary site of definitive hematopoiesis.

name: trunk ganglion
description: Ganglion which is located in the trunk.

name: neural keel
description: An intermediate stage (between the neural plate and neural rod) during the early segmentation period in the morphogenesis of the central nervous system primordium; the keel is roughly triangular shaped in cross section.

name: rectouterine fold
description: These folds of the rectouterine excavation are named the sacrogenital or rectouterine folds. They contain a considerable amount of fibrous tissue and non-striped muscular fibers which are attached to the front of the sacrum and constitute the uterosacral ligaments.
synonyms: ["fold of Douglas","plica rectouterina","posterior ligament of uterus","recto-uterine fold","rectovaginal fold"]

name: parietal mesothelium
description: Mesothelium overs the body walls is called the parietal mesothelium

name: visceral mesothelium
description: Mesothelium that covers the internal organs is called visceral mesothelium

name: left internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a left common carotid artery plus branches.

name: right internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a right common carotid artery plus branches.

name: embryonic post-anal tail
description: An embryonic structure that will either develop into a post-anal tail or recede into a vestigial remnant of the tail.

name: posterior spinal artery
description: A spinal artery that arises from the vertebral artery, adjacent to the medulla oblongata.

name: lumen of midgut
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a midgut.

name: lumen of hindgut
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a hindgut.

name: inferior thyroid artery
description: One of the three branches of the thyroid axis that supplies the thyroid gland and branches to form the ascending cervical, esophageal, inferior laryngeal, muscular and tracheal arteries.

name: superior thyroid artery
description: The superior thyroid artery arises from the external carotid artery just below the level of the greater cornu of the hyoid bone and ends in the thyroid gland.

name: mitral valve leaflet
description: A valve leafleft that is part of a mitral valve.
synonyms: ["leaflet of mitral valve","mitral valve leaflet","mitral valvular leaflet"]

name: inferior sagittal sinus
description: An intracranial venous sinus that lies in a midline location along the lower free border of the falx cerebri of the brain. The sinus receives blood from the great cerebral vein and joins the superior sagittal sinus posteriorly.

name: superior epigastric artery
description: An artery that arises from the internal thoracic arteryand anastomoses with the inferior epigastric artery at the umbilicus and supplies the anterior part of the abdominal wall and some of the diaphragm.

name: inferior epigastric vein
description: The blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood that arises from the superior epigastric vein and empties into the external iliac vein.

name: superior epigastric vein
description: A vein that drains into the internal thoracic vein, anastomosing with the inferior epigastric vein at the level of the umbilicus and drains the anterior part of the abdominal wall and some of the diaphragm. Along its course, it is accompanied by a similarly named artery, the superior epigastric artery.

name: inferior thyroid vein
description: The inferior thyroid veins two, frequently three or four, in number, arise in the venous plexus on the thyroid gland, communicating with the middle and superior thyroid veins. They form a plexus in front of the trachea, behind the Sternothyreoidei. From this plexus, a left vein descends and joins the left innominate trunk, and a right vein passes obliquely downward and to the right across the innominate artery to open into the right innominate vein, just at its junction with the superior vena cava; sometimes the right and left veins open by a common trunk in the latter situation. These veins receive esophageal tracheal, and inferior laryngeal veins, and are provided with valves at their terminations in the innominate veins.

name: superior thyroid vein
description: The superior thyroid vein begins in the substance and on the surface of the thyroid gland, by tributaries corresponding with the branches of the superior thyroid artery, and ends in the upper part of the internal jugular vein. It receives the superior laryngeal and cricothyroid veins.

name: lumen of anal canal
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a anal canal.

name: lumen of colon
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a colon.

name: inferior petrosal sinus
description: The inferior petrosal sinus, within the human head, is an area beneath the brain, which allows blood veins to span the area, from the center of the head downward. It drains from the cavernous sinus (beneath the brain) to the sigmoid sinuses above the internal jugular vein.

name: medial arcuate ligament
description: The medial arcuate ligament (also medial lumbocostal arch) is tendinous fascia that arches over the psoas major muscle as it passes through the diaphragm.

name: lateral arcuate ligament
description: The lateral arcuate ligament (also lateral lumbocostal arch) is a ligament under the diaphragm that arches across the upper part of the quadratus lumborum. It is traversed by the subcostal nerve, artery and vein.

name: superior nasal meatus
description: The superior meatus, the smallest of the three meatuses of the nose, occupies the middle third of the lateral wall of the nasal cavity. It lies between the superior nasal conchC& and middle nasal conchC&; the sphenopalatine foramen opens into it behind, and the posterior ethmoidal cells in front. The sphenoidal sinus opens into a recess, the sphenoethmoidal recess, which is placed above and behind the superior concha.

name: distal radio-ulnar joint
description: The Distal Radioulnar Articulation (inferior radioulnar joint) is a pivot-joint formed between the head of the ulna and the ulnar notch on the distal radius.
synonyms: ["articulation radioulnaris distalis","distal radioulnar joint","inferior radioulnar joint","radio-ulnar joint"]

name: proximal radio-ulnar joint
description: The proximal radioulnar articulation (superior radioulnar joint) is a trochoid or pivot joint between the circumference of the head of the radius and the ring formed by the radial notch of the ulna and the annular ligament.

name: long head of biceps brachii
description: The long head originates on the supraglenoid tubercle just above the shoulder joint from where its tendon passes down along the intertubercular groove of the humerus into the joint capsule of the shoulder joint. When the humerus is in motion, the tendon of the long head is held firmly in place in the intertubercular groove by the greater and lesser tubercles and the overlying transverse humeral ligament. During the motion from external to internal rotation, the tendon is forced medially against the lesser tubercle and superiorly against the transverse ligament.
synonyms: ["caput longum (musculus biceps brachii)","caput longum musculus bicipitis brachii"]

name: short head of biceps brachii
description: Proximally (towards the body), the short head of the biceps attaches to (originates from) the coracoid process at the top of the scapula.
synonyms: ["caput breve (musculus biceps brachii)","caput breve musculus bicipitis brachii"]

name: squamous part of occipital bone
description: The squama of the occipital bone, situated above and behind the foramen magnum, is curved from above downward and from side to side.
synonyms: ["occipital squama","occipital squama","squama occipitalis","squama of occipital bone"]

name: lateral border of scapula
description: The lateral border (or axillary border, or margin) is the thickest of the three borders of the scapula. It begins above at the lower margin of the glenoid cavity, and inclines obliquely downward and backward to the inferior angle. Immediately below the glenoid cavity is a rough impression, the infraglenoid tuberosity, about 2.5 cm. in length, which gives origin to the long head of the Triceps brachii; in front of this is a longitudinal groove, which extends as far as the lower third of this border, and affords origin to part of the Subscapularis. The inferior third is thin and sharp, and serves for the attachment of a few fibers of the Teres major behind, and of the Subscapularis in front.
synonyms: ["axillary border of scapula","lateral border of scapula","margo lateralis (scapula)","margo lateralis scapulae"]

name: medial border of scapula
description: The medial border of the scapula (vertebral border, medial margin) is the longest of the three borders, and extends from the medial to the inferior angle. It is arched, intermediate in thickness between the superior and the axillary borders, and the portion of it above the spine forms an obtuse angle with the part below. This border presents an anterior and a posterior lip, and an intermediate narrow area. The anterior lip affords attachment to the Serratus anterior; the posterior lip, to the Supraspinatus above the spine, the Infraspinatus below; the area between the two lips, to the Levator scapulC& above the triangular surface at the commencement of the spine, to the Rhomboideus minor on the edge of that surface, and to the Rhomboideus major below it; this last is attached by means of a fibrous arch, connected above to the lower part of the triangular surface at the base of the spine, and below to the lower part of the border.
synonyms: ["margo medialis (scapula)","margo medialis scapulae","medial part of scapula","vertebral border of scapula"]

name: inferior angle of scapula
description: An angle of the scapula formed by the union of the vertebral and axillary borders; its dorsal surface affords attachment to the Teres major and frequently to a few fibers of the Latissimus dorsi.

name: superior angle of scapula
description: An angle of the scapula formed by the junction of the superior and vertebral borders. It is thin, smooth, rounded, inclined somewhat lateralward, and gives attachment to a few fibers of the Levator scapulae
synonyms: ["angulus superior (scapula)","angulus superior scapulae","medial angle of scapula","superior medial angle of scapula"]

name: lamina propria of mucosa of colon
description: A lamina propria that is part of a colonic mucosa.
synonyms: ["colonic lamina propria","lamina propria mucosae of colon","lamina propria of colonic mucosa","lamina propria of colonic mucous membrane"]

name: muscularis mucosae of colon
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a colonic mucosa.
synonyms: ["lamina muscularis of colonic mucosa","lamina muscularis of colonic mucous membrane","muscularis mucosa of colon"]

name: serosa of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A serous membrane that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.
synonyms: ["serosa of infundibulum of fallopian tube","serosa of infundibulum of oviduct"]

name: muscle layer of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A muscle layer that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.
synonyms: ["muscle layer of infundibulum of fallopian tube","muscle layer of infundibulum of oviduct","muscularis of infundibulum of uterine tube"]

name: pericardio-peritoneal canal mesothelium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a pericardio-peritoneal canal.

name: pericardial visceral mesothelium
description: A visceral mesothelium that is part of a pericardium.
synonyms: ["mesothelium of visceral pericardium","mesothelium of visceral serous pericardium","visceral serous pericardium mesothelium"]

name: pericardial parietal mesothelium
description: A parietal mesothelium that is part of a pericardium.
synonyms: ["mesothelium of parietal pericardium","mesothelium of parietal serous pericardium","parietal serous pericardium mesothelium","pericardium parietal mesothelium"]

name: mesothelium of serous pericardium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a serous pericardium.

name: orbital gyrus
description: The inferior or orbital surface of the frontal lobe is concave, and rests on the orbital plate of the frontal bone. It is divided into four orbital gyri by a well-marked H-shaped orbital sulcus. These are named, from their position, the medial, anterior, lateral, and posterior orbital gyri. The medial orbital gyrus presents a well-marked antero-posterior sulcus, the olfactory sulcus, for the olfactory tract; the portion medial to this is named the straight gyrus, and is continuous with the superior frontal gyrus on the medial surface.

name: vesicular gland
description: The vesicular gland is part of the male reproductive system. The vesicular gland contributes fluids, energy substrates, and buffers to semen. It can be found near the Coagulating gland, which also belongs to the reproductive system.

name: stroma of bone marrow
description: The stroma of the bone marrow is all tissue not directly involved in the primary function of hematopoiesis. The yellow bone marrow belongs here, and makes the majority of the bone marrow stroma, in addition to stromal cells located in the red bone marrow. Yellow bone marrow is found in the Medullary cavity. Still, the stroma is indirectly involved in hematopoiesis, since it provides the hematopoietic microenvironment that facilitates hematopoiesis by the parenchymal cells. For instance, they generate colony stimulating factors, affecting hematopoiesis.

name: tracheobronchial tree
description: The structure from the trachea, bronchi, and bronchioles that forms the airways that supply air to the lungs. The lining of the tracheobronchial tree consists of ciliated columnar epithelial cells.

name: hermaphroditic organism
description: multicellular organism that can produce both male and female gametes.

name: hermaphrodite anatomical structure
description: An anatomical structure present only in hermaphrodites.

name: brachiocephalic vasculature
description: The vasculature consisting of brachiocephalic arteries and veins.

name: mesenchyme derived from head neural crest
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a cranial neural crest.
synonyms: ["head mesenchyme from cranial neural crest","head mesenchyme from neural crest","head neural crest derived mesenchyme"]

name: mesenchyme derived from trunk neural crest
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a trunk neural crest.
synonyms: ["trunk mesenchyme from neural crest","trunk neural crest derived mesenchyme"]

name: trabecula cranii
description: Paired thin medially aligned bar of cartilage that extends from the anterior end of the chondrocranium to just anterior to the anterior end of the notochord. The posterior ends of the trabeculae cranii are continuous with the parachordal cartilages, and they enclose the hypophyseal fenestra.

name: late embryonic stage
description: An embryo stage that covers late steps of the embryogenesis with a fully formed embryo still developing before birth or egg hatching.

name: neonate stage
description: Of or pertaining to the period of time immediately following birth, or to the newborn.

name: osseus cochlea
description: The osseous cochlea is the bony foundation that forms the small shell arrangement for the cochlear nerve.

name: medial entorhinal cortex
description: One of two subdivisions of the entorhinal cortex, located medially.

name: lateral entorhinal cortex
description: One of two subdivisions of the entorhinal cortex, located laterally.

name: superior vestibular nucleus
description: The superior vestibular nucleus is the dorso-lateral part of the vestibular nucleus and receives collaterals and terminals from the ascending branches of the vestibular nerve. Its axons terminate in much the same manner as do those from the lateral nucleus.

name: vestibular nucleus
description: A cranial nucleus for the vestibular nerve..
synonyms: ["vestibular nucleus of acoustic nerve","vestibular nucleus of eighth cranial nerve","vestibular VIII nucleus"]

name: lateral vestibular nucleus
description: One of the nuclei comprising the vestibular nuclear complex. In some mammals, e.g., primates, it is further subdivided into subnuclei. It therefore differs in appearance and topology in different mammals.
synonyms: ["Deiter's nucleus","Deiters' nucleus","lateral nucleus of Deiters","nucleus of Deiters"]

name: tunica media of artery
description: A tunica media that is part of a artery.

name: tunica adventitia of artery
description: A tunica adventitia that is part of a artery.

name: tunica adventitia of vein
description: A tunica adventitia that is part of a vein.

name: tunica intima of vein
description: A tunica intima that is part of a vein.

name: tunica media of vein
description: A tunica media that is part of a vein.

name: inferior olivary nucleus
description: The inferior olivary nucleus is the largest nucleus situated in the olivary body, part of the medulla oblongata.

name: nuclear complex of neuraxis
description: Gray matter of the central nervous system which is a collection of clustered nuclei.

name: nucleus of superior olivary complex
description: Any of the nuclei that comprise the superior olivary complex (superior olive). This includes both the primary nuclei such as the lateral and medial nuclei, as well as periolivary nuclei.

name: dorsal accessory inferior olivary nucleus
description: The inferior olivary nucleus that is the smallest, and appears on transverse section as a curved lamina behind the primary olivary nucleus
synonyms: ["DAO","dorsal accessory olivary nucleus","dorsal accessory olive","inferior olivary complex, dorsal accessory olive","inferior olive, dorsal nucleus","nucleus olivaris accessorius posterior","posterior accessory olivary nucleus"]

name: lingual tonsil
description: the lymph tissue on the floor of the oropharyngeal passage, near the root of the tongue

name: preoptic nucleus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a preoptic area.

name: intervertebral disk of cervical vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a cervical region of vertebral column. A cervical intervertebral disk connects at least one cervical vertebra, either to another cervical vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a thoracic vertebra
synonyms: ["cervical intervertebral disc","intervertebral disc of cervical region"]

name: intervertebral disk of thoracic vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a thoracic region of vertebral column. A thoracic intervertebral disk connects at least one thoracic vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a lumbar vertebra

name: intervertebral disk of lumbar vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a lumbar region of vertebral column. A lumbar intervertebral disk connects at least one lumbar vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a sacral vertebra

name: intervertebral disk of sacral vertebra
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a sacral region of vertebral column. A sacral intervertebral disk connects at least one sacral vertebra, either to another thoracic vertebra, or at one point on the vertebral colummn, to a sacral vertebra

name: intervertebral disk of third cervical vertebra
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 3 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 4.

name: intervertebral disk of fourth cervical vertebra
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 4 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 5.
synonyms: ["intervertebral disc of fourth cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk, C4-C5"]

name: intervertebral disk of fifth cervical vertebra
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 5 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 6.
synonyms: ["intervertebral disc of fifth cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk, C5-C6"]

name: intervertebral disk of sixth cervical vertebra
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 6 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 7.

name: intervertebral disk of seventh cervical vertebra
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a thoracic vertebra and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 7.

name: intervertebral disk of axis
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a vertebral bone 2 and connects a mammalian cervical vertebra 3.
synonyms: ["C2 disk","C2 intervertebral disk","intervertebral disc of cervical vertebra 2","intervertebral disc of second cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk of cervical vertebra 2","intervertebral disk of second cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk, C2-C3","second cervical intervertebral disk"]

name: intervertebral disk of atlas
description: A intervertebral disk that connects a vertebral bone 1 and connects a vertebral bone 2.
synonyms: ["C1 disk","C1 intervertebral disk","first cervical intervertebral disk","intervertebral disc of cervical vertebra 1","intervertebral disc of first cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk of cervical vertebra 1","intervertebral disk of first cervical vertebra","intervertebral disk, C1-C2"]

name: trachea pre-cartilage rings
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a trachea.

name: upper esophageal sphincter
description: The upper esophageal sphincter (UES) (also called the Pharyngoesophageal sphincter) refers to the superior portion of the esophagus. Unlike the lower esophageal sphincter, it consists of striated muscle and is under conscious control. The primary muscle of the UES is the cricopharyngeus portion of the inferior pharyngeal constrictor. During swallowing the upper esophageal sphincter opens so the bolus can pass into the esophagus. A secondary role of the UES is to reduce backflow from the esophagus into the pharynx.
synonyms: ["pharyngoesophageal sphincter","upper esophageal sphincter muscle","upper oesophageal sphincter"]

name: pectoral appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: pelvic appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a pelvic appendage.

name: appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of an appendage.

name: pectoral appendage skeleton
description: Skeletal subdivision consisting of the anterior appendicular limb skeleton, excluding the pectoral girdle.

name: pelvic appendage skeleton
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in a pelvic appendage region.

name: crista of ampulla of anterior semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a anterior semicircular duct.
synonyms: ["anterior crista ampullaris","anterior cristae","anterior semicircular canal sensory patch","anterior semicircular canal sensory patches","rostral crista"]

name: crista of ampulla of posterior semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a posterior semicircular duct.
synonyms: ["caudal crista","posterior crista ampullaris","posterior cristae","posterior semicircular canal sensory patch","posterior semicircular canal sensory patches"]

name: crista of ampulla of lateral semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a lateral semicircular duct.
synonyms: ["lateral crista ampullaris","lateral cristae","lateral semicircular canal sensory patch","lateral semicircular canal sensory patches"]

name: presumptive hindbrain
description: The rhombencephalon (or hindbrain) is a developmental categorization of portions of the central nervous system in vertebrates. The rhombencephalon can be subdivided in a variable number of transversal swellings called rhombomeres. In the human embryo eight rhombomeres can be distinguished, from caudal to rostral: Rh7-Rh1 and the isthmus (the most rostral rhombomere). A rare disease of the rhombencephalon, 'rhombencephalosynapsis' is characterized by a missing vermis resulting in a fused cerebellum. Patients generally present with cerebellar ataxia. The caudal rhombencephalon has been generally considered as the initiation site for neural tube closure.

name: presumptive sinus venosus
description: Portion of tissue that is part of the heart tube and will become the sinus venosus.

name: presumptive atrioventricular canal
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a atrioventricular canal.

name: presumptive endocardium
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a endocardium.

name: presumptive midbrain hindbrain boundary
description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the midbrain hindbrain boundary.

name: presumptive segmental plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a presomitic mesoderm.

name: presumptive shield
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a primitive knot.

name: presumptive neural plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a neural plate.

name: presumptive paraxial mesoderm
description: The part of the blastula that has the potential to develop into a paraxial mesoderm.

name: presumptive floor plate
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a floor plate.

name: presumptive bulbus arteriosus
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a bulbus arteriosus.

name: presumptive forebrain midbrain boundary
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a forebrain-midbrain boundary.

name: presumptive rhombomere 1
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 1.

name: presumptive rhombomere 3
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 3.

name: presumptive rhombomere 4
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 4.

name: presumptive rhombomere 5
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 5.

name: presumptive rhombomere 6
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 6.

name: presumptive rhombomere 7
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 7.

name: presumptive rhombomere 8
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 8.

name: presumptive rhombomere 2
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 2.

name: presumptive pronephric mesoderm
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a pronephric mesoderm.

name: pronephric proximal convoluted tubule
description: A proximal convoluted tubule that is part of a pronephros.

name: choroid plexus of tectal ventricle
description: A choroid plexus that is part of a cerebral aqueduct.

name: pectoral appendage blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: appendage blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a limb/fin.

name: pectoral appendage vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: pharyngeal vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a chordate pharynx.

name: appendage vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a limb/fin.

name: pronephric glomerular capillary
description: A glomerular capillary that is part of a pronephros.

name: pronephric glomerular basement membrane
description: A glomerular basement membrane that is part of a pronephros.

name: pronephric distal early tubule
description: A distal early tubule that is part of a pronephros.

name: sputum
description: Matter ejected from the lungs, bronchi, and trachea, through the mouth.

name: pudendal artery
description: Either the internal or external pudendal arteries.

name: internal pudendal artery
