description: The pars reflexa is a separable part of the superficial masseter muscle that attaches to the medial surface of the mandible.

name: body of mandible
description: The zone of the mandible that carries the teeth.

name: masseteric fossa
description: .The fossa for the masseter. In some therapsids, the coronoid process of the dentary bears a large external depression which accommodates the masseter -- an important muscle in closing and in grinding motions of the jaw.

name: hyoepiglottic ligament
description: An elastic band connecting the anterior surface of the epiglottis to the upper border of the body of the hyoid bone.

name: digastric branch of facial nerve
description: The digastric branch of facial nerve arises close to the stylomastoid foramen, and divides into several filaments, which supply the posterior belly of the Digastricus; one of these filaments joins the glossopharyngeal nerve.
synonyms: ["digastric branch","digastric branch of facial nerve (CN VII)","facial nerve, digastric branch","nerve to posterior belly of digastric","ramus digastricus (nervus facialis)","ramus digastricus nervus facialis"]

name: nerve to stylohyoid from facial nerve
description: The stylohyoid branch of facial nerve frequently arises in conjunction with the digastric branch; it is long and slender, and enters the Stylohyoideus about its middle.
synonyms: ["facial nerve stylohyoid branch","nerve to stylohyoid","ramus stylohyoideus","ramus stylohyoideus nervus facialis","stylodigastric nerve","stylohyoid branch of facial nerve"]

name: nerve to stylopharyngeus from glossopharyngeal nerve
description: The stylopharyngeal branch of glossopharyngeal nerve is distributed to the Stylopharyngeus.
synonyms: ["branch of glossopharyngeal nerve to stylopharyngeus","nerve to stylopharyngeus","ramus musculi stylopharyngei nervus glossopharyngei","stylopharyngeal branch of glossopharyngeal nerve"]

name: capsule of temporomandibular joint
description: The articular capsule (capsular ligament) is a thin, loose envelope, attached above to the circumference of the mandibular fossa and the articular tubercle immediately in front; below, to the neck of the condyle of the mandible.
synonyms: ["articular capsule of temporomandibular joint","capsula articularis articulationis temporomandibularis"]

name: disk of temporomandibular joint
description: The fibrocartilaginous plate that separates the joint into upper and lower cavities.
synonyms: ["articular disc of temporomandibular joint","articular disk of temporomandibular joint","discus articularis (articulatio temporomandibularis)","discus articularis articulationis temporomandibularis","discus articularis articulationis temporomandibularis","temporomandibular articular disk"]

name: masseteric nerve
description: A muscular branch of the mandibular nerve passing to the medial surface of the masseter muscle, which it innervates.

name: mylohyoid nerve
description: A nerve that innervates the mylohyoid muscle and the anterior belly of the digastric muscle.
synonyms: ["branch of inferior alveolar nerve to mylohyoid","mylodigastric nerve","mylohyoid branch of inferior alveolar nerve","nerve to mylohyoid","nervus mylohyoideus","nervus mylohyoideus"]

name: pharyngeal nerve plexus
description: The pharyngeal plexus is a network of nerve fibers innervating most of the palate, larynx, and pharynx. It is located on the surface of the middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle.
synonyms: ["pharyngeal nerve plexus","pharyngeal plexus of vagus nerve","plexus pharyngeus nervi vagi","vagus nerve pharyngeal plexus"]

name: superior laryngeal nerve
description: The superior laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve. It arises from the middle of the ganglion nodosum and in its course receives a branch from the superior cervical ganglion of the sympathetic. It descends, by the side of the pharynx, behind the internal carotid artery, and divides into two branches: external laryngeal nerve internal laryngeal nerve A superior laryngeal nerve palsy changes the pitch of the voice and causes an inability to make explosive sounds. If no recovery is evident three months after the palsy initially presents, the damage is most likely to be permanent. A bilateral palsy presents as a tiring and hoarse voice.
synonyms: ["nervus laryngealis superior","nervus laryngeus superior","superior laryngeal branch of inferior vagal ganglion","superior laryngeal branch of vagus"]

name: deep temporal nerve
description: The deep temporal nerves, branches of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve, are two in number, anterior and posterior. They pass above the upper border of the pterygoideus externus and enter the deep surface of the temporalis.

name: surface of mandible
description: A anatomical surface that is part of a mandible.

name: lateral surface of mandible
synonyms: ["lateral surface of mandibular ramus","lateral surface of ramus of mandible"]

name: pharyngeal raphe
description: The Pharyngeal raphe is a raphe that serves as the origin and insertion for several of the pharyngeal constrictors.

name: palatine raphe
description: A raphe running across the palate, from the palatine uvula to the incisive papilla.

name: raphe of hard palate
description: A palatine raphe that is part of a hard palate.

name: raphe of soft palate
description: A palatine raphe that is part of a soft palate.

name: pterygomandibular raphe
description: The pterygomandibular raphe (pterygomandibular ligament) is a tendinous band of the buccopharyngeal fascia, attached by one extremity to the hamulus of the medial pterygoid plate, and by the other to the posterior end of the mylohyoid line of the mandible. Its medial surface is covered by the mucous membrane of the mouth. Its lateral surface is separated from the ramus of the mandible by a quantity of adipose tissue. Its posterior border gives attachment to the superior pharyngeal constrictor muscle. Its anterior border attaches to the posterior edge of the buccinator.

name: Reissner's fiber
description: An acellular strand that runs from subcommissural organ caudally through the ventricular system and central canal to the ampulla caudalis. Develops from glycoproteins secreted into CSF.

name: urophysis
description: This is a neurosecretory organ rostral to the ampulla caudalis on the ventral surface of the distal end of the spinal cord. Receives axons from caudal neurosecretory nucleus, which contains Dahlgren cells that secrete urotensin I and II, implicated in osmotic regulation, cardiovascular function and reproduction.

name: ampulla caudalis
description: A ventricle-like space at the end of the central canal

name: cranial blood vasculature
description: A blood vasculature that is part of a head.
synonyms: ["cranial blood vessel","set of blood vessels of head"]

name: cranial lymph vasculature
description: A lymph vasculature that is part of a head.
synonyms: ["cranial lymph vessel","cranial lymphatics","set of lymphatic vessels of head"]

name: cleidocephalicus muscle
description: The cleidomastoideus is a thick, strap-like muscle that together with the cleidocervicalis forms the proximal part of the brachiocephalicus. It lies beneath the cleidocervicalis. Its origin is the clavicular tendon with its insertion being at the mastoid process of the temporal bone. It is distinctly narrow and is united with the cleidocervicalis and cleidobrachialis by the clavicular tendon. Together with the other two components of the brachiocephalicus muscle, its primary function is to advance the free limb, however, it can also act as an shoulder extensor. Acting bilaterally, it fixes and depresses the neck, while by its unilateral action, it allows the head and neck to be drawn to the side. Its blood supply is the inferior cervical, carotid and vertebral arteries and its nerve supply is the spinal accessory, cervical and axillary nerves.

name: cleidobrachialis muscle
description: This muscle makes up the distal segment of the brachiocephalicus. It originates at the clavicular tendon but functionally, from the head and neck through the cleidocervicalis. It inserts at the distal end of the cranial border of the humerus, where it lies between the biceps brachii medially and the brachialis laterally. The muscle partly covers the pectoral muscles at their insertions. In conjunction with the cleidocervicalis, it advances the limb, extends the shoulder and causes lateral movement of the head and neck.

name: brachiocephalic muscle
description: The brachiocephalicus is a long and flat, complex of muscles that extends from the lower half of the humeral shaft to the head and neck. The muscle divides into two parts at the clavicular intersection. This is also the point of origin for all the muscles that make up the brachiocephalicus. This point is situated just cranial to the shoulder. The two main sections are the cleidobrachialis which is distal to the clavicular intersection and the cleidocephalicus which extends proximally to the clavivular intersection. The cleidocephalicus can also be divided into the pars cervicalis, which inserts on the broad aponeurosis, over the fibrous raphe of the cranial half of the neck. The other part, the pars mastoideus inserts on the mastoid process of the temporal bone via a strong tendon. The cleidobrachialis extends distally from the clavicular intersection and inserts on the cranial edge of the distal half of the humerus. The tendon that inserts the cleidobrachialis lies between the brachialis muscle and the biceps brachii. As a result of the brachiocephalicus spanning a large region it has the ability to provide a number of actions. These include extending the shoulder joint, protracts the limb, provides lateral movement of the head and allows the neck to be depressed.

name: omotransversarius muscle
description: The omotransversarius is a straplike muscle, which advances and adducts the forelimb, as well as flexes the neck laterally. It covers the transverse processes of the cervical vertebrae, lying to their side. The omotransversarius lies ventral to the trapezius, cranial to the deltoid muscle and is covered cranially by the cleidocervicalis. It extends from the atlas to the spine of the scapula, with its origin on the transverse process of the atlas and its insertion in the distal end of the spine of the scapula. Its name can be split into omo, which is Greek for shoulder, and tranversarius which relates to its attachment to the transverse process of the atlas. This muscle is innervated by the accessory nerve.

name: transverse process of atlas
description: A transverse process of vertebra that is part of a vertebral bone 1.

name: sternocephalicus muscle
description: The sternocephalicus is a flat muscle and its caudal border is adjacent to the ventral border of the brachiocephalicus. The lateral aspect of this muscle is crossed obliquely by the external jugular vein. It originates as a unit on the first sternebrae. The cranial portion of the muscle divides into two separate sections with different insertion points. These are the sternomastoideus and the sterno-occipitalis. The ventral portion, the sternomastiodeus is the stronger and main continuation of the sternocephalicus, which inserts on the mastoid part of the temporal bone. The thin but wide dorsal segment, the sterno-occipitalis attaches to the dorsal nuchal crest by a thin aponeurosis. The main action provided by the sternocephalicus is movement of the head and neck to the side. Ventral branches of the cervical nerves are attached to this muscle.

name: prepuce
description: A retractable double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the glans penis or clitoris. Glands may also be present.

name: skin of prepuce of clitoris
description: A zone of skin that is part of a prepuce of clitoris.

name: iliothoracic muscle
description: The iliothoracic group is made up of the abdominal wall muscles: rectus abdominis, external abdominal oblique, internal abdominal obliquus, and the transversus abdominis

name: femorothoracic muscle
description: The femorospinal group is made up of the psoas major and iliacus muscles

name: male external urethral sphincter
description: The external sphincter muscle of urethra (or sphincter urethrae membranaceae) surrounds the whole length of the membranous portion of the urethra, and is enclosed in the fasciæ of the urogenital diaphragm. They arch across the front of the urethra and bulbourethral glands, pass around the urethra, and behind it unite with the muscle of the opposite side, by means of a tendinous raphé.
synonyms: ["external urethral sphincter of male urethra","male sphincter urethrae","male sphincter urethrae muscle","male urethral sphincter muscle","musculus sphincter urethrae externus (urethra masculina)","musculus sphincter urethrae externus urethrae masculinae","musculus sphincter urethrae membranaceae"]

name: female external urethral sphincter
description: The external sphincter muscle of female urethra is a muscle which controls urination.
synonyms: ["external urethral sphincter of female urethra","musculus sphincter urethrae externus (urethra feminina)","musculus sphincter urethrae externus urethrae femininae","outer muscle layer of female urethra","rhabdosphincter of female urethra","striated muscle layer of female urethra"]

name: inferior pancreaticoduodenal vein
description: A blood vessel running parallel to the inferior pancreatico-duodenal artery that drains blood from the pancreas and duodenum into the splenic vein.

name: parotidoauricular muscle
description: Is one of the numerus muscles of the external ear and is of importance since it is encountered in the operation for drainage of infections of the external ear of the dog. As its name suggests, it arises from the fascia over the parotid gland and approaches the auricle from the ventrolateral direction. This muscle is supplied by the facial nerve.The muscles of the external ear with their scattered origins and precisely located insertions provide for displacement and rotation of the ear in all directions. These muscles also have a collective function in communication both within and between species.

name: facial modiolus
description: A chiasma of facial muscles held together by fibrous tissue, located lateral and slightly superior to each angle of the mouth. It is important in moving the mouth, facial expression and in dentistry. It derives its motor nerve supply from the facial nerve, and its blood supply from labial branches of the facial artery. It is contributed to by the following muscles: orbicularis oris, buccinator, levator anguli oris, depressor anguli oris, zygomaticus major, risorius quadratus labii superioris, quadratus labii inferioris.

name: male bulbospongiosus muscle
description: A bulbospongiosus muscle that is part of a male reproductive system.

name: bulbospongiosus muscle
description: The bulbospongiosus is the thick extrapelvic continuation of the urethralis. It originates from the perineal body (and midline raphe over corpus spongiosum in male) and inserts at the superficial perineal membrane and dorsal penile or clitoral aponeurosis. In males, the bulbospongiosus muscles are united and surround the base of the penis. They aid in emptying of urine and ejaculate from urethra. In females, these muscles are separated in the middle by the vagina and act to constrict the vaginal introitus. They can also stop the flow of blood into veins, which maintains an erection in the penis of the male and the clitoris of the female. Its nerve connection is the perineal branch of the pudendal nerve (S2, 3, 4).

name: pudendal nerve
description: The pudendal nerve is a somatic nerve in the pelvic region that innervates the external genitalia of both sexes, as well as sphincters for the bladder and the rectum. It originates in Onuf's nucleus in the sacral region of the spinal cord.

name: perineal nerve
description: A nerve arising from the pudendal nerve that supplies the perineum.

name: blood vessel internal elastic membrane
description: A layer of elastic tissue that forms the outermost part of the tunica intima of blood vessels.
synonyms: ["inner elastic lamina","internal elastic lamina","internal elastic membrane"]

name: cutaneous trunci muscle
description: Lying just below the skin, cutaneus trunci is one of very few cutaneus muscles. It composes of a thin sheets of muscle that spred over the body in the superficial fasciae. Their role is to twich the skin to rid of pests etc. Cuteneus muscles are found in all domestic species.

name: levator nasolabialis muscle
description: Is a principal muscle of the lips which arises over the dorsum of the nose. It runs cranioventrally to insert partly on the wing of the nostril and partly into the lateral part of the upper lip. This muscles function includes dilation of the nostril, elevation and retraction of the upper lip. Branches of the facial nerve supply innervation to this muscle.

name: longissimus atlantis muscle
description: A muscle that runs beneath the longissimus capitis and inserts on the wing of the atlas

name: ventral lateral sacrocaudal muscle
description: The ventral lateral sacrocaudal is a long strong muscle consisting of numerous individual parts. Its first segment originates from the last lumbar vertebrae and the remainder from the transverse processes of the caudal vertebrae. From the segmented bellies arise long tendons which are embedded in caudal fascia. The first of these tendons inserts onto the sixth caudal vertebrae, the second onto the seventh and so on until the last caudal vertebrae. The ventral lateral sacrocaudal acts to flex the tail and occasionally assists with lateral movement.

name: rectus thoracis muscle
description: Rectus thoracis is a very small quadrilateral muscle sheet from the lateral thorax runs from the 3rd-1st rib that is in continuation with rectus abdominis. Its functioning muscle in respiration.

name: sphincter colli superficialis muscle
description: The sphincter colli superficialis is composed of transverse muscle fibers, and covers the entire area between the lower jaw and chest. The muscle is used to tighten the skin on the underside of the throat.

name: sphincter colli profundus muscle
description: The sphincter colli profundus lies below the platysma in the area of the parotid gland (gland regions).

name: cloacal bursa
description: An evagination of the cloaca. In Testudines these are hypothesized to function in different physiological roles, primarily in respiration.

name: iliococcygeus muscle
description: The Iliococcygeus arises from the ischial spine and from the posterior part of the tendinous arch of the obturator fascia, and is attached to the coccyx and anococcygeal raphC); it is usually thin, and may fail entirely, or be largely replaced by fibrous tissue. It is part of the levator ani group of muscles. An accessory slip at its posterior part is sometimes named the Iliosacralis.

name: puborectalis muscle
description: The fibers which form a sling for the rectum are named the Puborectalis or Sphincter recti. They arise from the lower part of the symphysis pubis, and from the superior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm. They meet with the corresponding fibers of the opposite side around the lower part of the rectum, and form for it a strong sling. Relaxation reduces the angle between rectum and anus, allowing defecation in conjunction with relaxation of the internal and external sphincters. Puborectalis is part of the levator ani group of muscles.

name: pubococcygeus muscle
description: The pubococcygeus muscle or PC muscle is a hammock-like muscle, found in both sexes, that stretches from the pubic bone to the coccyx (tail bone) forming the floor of the pelvic cavity and supporting the pelvic organs. It is part of the levator ani group of muscles.

name: male pubococcygeus muscle
description: A pubococcygeus muscle that is part of a male organism.

name: female pubococcygeus muscle
description: Pubovaginalis in the female is the equivalent of levator prostatae in the male.

name: abductor pollicis, radioulna-prepollox
description: Originates on the distal radioulna and inserts on the palmar prepollex.

name: chondroglossus muscle
description: The Chondroglossus is sometimes described as a part of the Hyoglossus, but is separated from it by fibers of the Genioglossus, which pass to the side of the pharynx. It is about 2 cm. long, and arises from the medial side and base of the lesser cornu and contiguous portion of the body of the hyoid bone, and passes directly upward to blend with the intrinsic muscular fibers of the tongue, between the Hyoglossus and Genioglossus.

name: adductor pollicis muscle of prepollex
description: Originates from the distal carpal 5-4-3 and inserts on the palmar prepollex.

name: lumen of gastrointestinal system
synonyms: ["cavity of digestive tract","cavity of gastrointestinal tract","gastrointestinal tract lumen","lumen of gastrointestinal tract"]

name: lumen of esophagus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a esophagus.
synonyms: ["cavity of eosophagus","cavity of esophagus","eosophageal cavity","eosophageal lumen","eosophagus lumen","esophageal cavity","esophageal lumen","esophagus lumen"]

name: mesonephric duct lumen
description: A tube lumen that is part of a mesonephric duct.

name: styloid process of ulna
description: The styloid process of the ulna projects from the medial and back part of the bone; it descends a little lower than the head, and its rounded end affords attachment to the ulnar collateral ligament of the wrist.
synonyms: ["processus styloideus ulnae","processus styloideus ulnae","ulnar styloid process"]

name: supraorbital ridge
description: the superior half of the orbital rim, which constitutes the curved superior border of the orbital opening, formed by the frontal bone.
synonyms: ["margo supraorbitalis","superior orbital rim","supra-orbital margin","supra-orbital ridge","supraorbital margin"]

name: flexural organ
description: A portion of tissue that is the most anterior portion of the notochord. The flexural organ secretes Reissner's fiber-related proteins, including F-spondin.

name: venom gland
description: A gland that secretes venom.

name: platypus crural gland
description: A kidney-shaped alveolar glands located in the upper thigh connected by a thin-walled duct to a calcaneus spur, or calcar, on each hind limb.

name: paired limb/fin skeleton
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in an individual limb or fin.
synonyms: ["limb/fin skeleton","skeletal parts of limb/fin","skeleton of limb/fin"]

name: stylopodial skeleton
description: Proximal element of a free limb skeleton consisting of the femur and humerus in the forelimb stylopodium and hindlimb stylopodium respectively.

name: zeugopodial skeleton
description: Section of the forelimb skeleton located between the stylopodium and the autopodium.

name: cell condensation
description: Anatomical structure that is an aggregation of similar cells from which cartilages and bones form, and from which chondrogenesis and osteogenesis are initiated during repair and/or regeneration. (Hall and Miyake 1995).

name: pre-dentine
description: Odontogenic tissue that is collagen-rich and characteristic of vertebrate teeth and tooth-like structures (e.g., odontodes) deposited by preodontoblasts and odontoblasts that are typically excluded from the matrix.

name: pre-enamel
description: Odontogenic tissue that is avascular non-mineralized matrix that is deposited by preameloblast and ameloblasts that are excluded from the matrix.

name: non-mineralized cartilage tissue
description: Cartilage tissue that is not mineralized.

name: commissure of diencephalon
description: A commissure that is part of a diencephalon.

name: tract of diencephalon
description: An axon tract that is part of a diencephalon.

name: maxillary tooth
description: A tooth that is attached to a maxilla.

name: dentary tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to a dentary/mandible.

name: jaw region
description: A subdivision of the head that corresponds to the jaw skeleton, containing both soft tissue, skeleton and teeth (when present). The jaw region is divided into upper and lower regions.

name: bone of upper jaw
description: Any bone that is part of the upper jaw skeleton. This includes (when present): the maxilla, the quadrate (in some species).

name: lenticular process of incus bone
description: The long ventral process of the incus bone which articulates with the stapes
synonyms: ["incus crus longum","lenticular process","lenticular process of incus","processus lenticularis","processus lenticularis (incus)","processus lenticularis incudis"]

name: gingiva of upper jaw
description: A gingiva that is part of a upper jaw region.
synonyms: ["gum of maxilla","gum of upper jaw","upper gingiva","upper jaw gingiva"]

name: gingiva of lower jaw
description: A gingiva that is part of a lower jaw region.
synonyms: ["gum of lower jaw","gum of mandible","lower gingiva","lower jaw gingiva"]

name: coronoid tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to a coronoid bone.

name: carina of sternum
description: An extension of the sternum (breastbone) which runs axially along the midline of the sternum and extends outward, perpendicular to the plane of the ribs.

name: supracoracoideus muscle of wing
description: A muscle in the bird's thorax region that originates from carina of the sternum, furcula, and sternal ribs and inserts onto proximal dorsal surface of the humerus. It acts as a primary elevator of the wing in upstroke..

name: hyomandibular bone
description: Replacement bone that is bilaterally paired and (in teleosts) articulates with the neurocranium dorsally and the opercle posteriorly.

name: hyomandibular cartilage
description: Cartilage form of the hyomandibular element.

name: hyomandibular element
description: The upper paired deep bone or cartilage of the hyoid region, sometimes taking part in jaw suspension and which supports the opercle. Dorsally it articulates with the otic capsule at the hyomandibular fossa, ventrally with the quadrate and symplectic. In most Teleostei it has a foramen for the hyomandibular branch of the facial nerve (VII).

name: hypohyal element
description: The hypohyal is a ventral element of the hyoid arch which links the ceratohyal and the basihyal.

name: basihyal element
description: Skeletal element that is median and is the anterior-most element of the ventral hyoid arch.

name: basihyal cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is median and is the anterior-most cartilage of the ventral hyoid arch.

name: basihyal bone
description: Replacement bone that is median and is the anterior-most bone of the ventral hyoid arch.

name: stylohyoid bone
description: This is the paired bone that makes up the segment of the mammalian hyoid apparatus connecting the epihyoids with the skull via the tympanohyoid cartilages on each side. Ventrally, it defines the medial and lateral compartments of the guttural pouch in the horse.

name: basihyal lingual process
description: A projection on the basihyal bone. Laterally the lingual process is compressed. It has a blunt pointed free end, and its lateral surfaces are slightly concave. The dorsal border is thin and irregular, and the ventral border is thick and rough. In the living animal the lingual process is embedded within the root of the tongue.
synonyms: ["lingual process of basihyoid","lingual process of basihyoid bone"]

name: thyrohyoid cartilage
description: This small finger of cartilage completes the connection between the thyrohyoid bone and the thyroid cartilage (rostral cornu)

name: thyrohyoid bone
description: Is a laterally bowed, sagittally compressed, slender element that extends from dorsocaudally from the lateral parts of the basihyoid. It connects the basiohyoid with the rostral corner of the thyroid cartlilage of the larynx.

name: superior horn of thyroid cartilage
description: The superior horn of thyroid cartilage is long and narrow, directed upward, backward, and medialward, and ends in a conical extremity, which gives attachment to the lateral hyothyroid ligament.
synonyms: ["cornu superius (cartilago thyroidea)","cornu superius cartilaginis thyroideae","superior cornu of thyroid cartilage"]

name: inferior horn of thyroid cartilage
description: The inferior horn of thyroid cartilage is short and thick; it is directed downward, with a slight inclination forward and medialward, and presents, on the medial side of its tip, a small oval articular facet for articulation with the side of the cricoid cartilage.
synonyms: ["cornu inferius (cartilago thyroidea)","cornu inferius cartilaginis thyroidea","cornu inferius cartilaginis thyroideae"]

name: tympanohyoid cartilage
description: The terminal segment in the chain of skeletal elements of the hyoid apparatus. One of a pair of rods of cartilage that connect the hyoid bone to the styloid process of the petrous part of the temporal bone

name: orbital part of frontal bone
description: A zone of the frontal bone that consists of two thin triangular plates, the orbital plates, which form the vaults of the orbits, and are separated from one another by a median gap, the ethmoidal notch.

name: ectopterygoid bone
description: A palatal bone which -- like many palatal bones -- may originally have developed as a dermal bone replacing part of the palatoquadrate, the primitive upper jaw. Like the palatine (also called dermopalatine), the ectopterygoid replaces the middle part of the autopalatine. It may be serially homologous with the palatine(s), but is somewhat specialized, being the last (most posterior in palatal view) of the series and bordering the fossa for the jaw muscles. In a typical tetrapod it abuts the palatine anteriorly, the maxilla laterally, the pterygoid or the fossa mandubuaris medially, and the fossa posteriorly

name: splenial bone
description: The splenial is a small bone in the lower jaw of reptiles, amphibians and birds, usually located on the lingual side (closest to the tongue) between the angular and suprangular.

name: surangular bone
description: The surangular is a dermal bone of the lower jaw. It typically covers much of the dorsal and lateral surface of the posterior jaw and variably extends onto the medial (inside) surface. The surangular articulates with and supports the articular, which forms the jaw joint with the quadrate in most vertebrates, and is in turn supported by the angular. More distally, the surangular bridges the mandibular fenestra, if one is present. It may also bear a raised dorsal coronoid process, an important attachment site for the mandibular adductors. At its distal (or rostral) end, the surangular meets the dentary, the main tooth-bearing bone of the lower jaw in most vertebrates.

name: prearticular bone
description: Osseous element of intramembranous origin that extends along the lingual margin of Meckel's cartilage.

name: frontoparietal bone
description: An anuran dermal bone that usually is paired and roofs the braincase.

name: palatoglossal arch
description: A fold that lies between the mouth and pharynx and marks the posterior border of the mouth
synonyms: ["anterior pillar of fauces","arcus glossopalatinus","arcus palatoglossus","glossopalatine arch","plica anterior faucium"]

name: odontogenic mesenchyme of molar
description: An odontogenic papilla that is part of a molar tooth.

name: oral epithelium from ectoderm
description: An epithelium that develops_from a ectoderm and is part of a oral epithelium.

name: puboischiofemoralis internus muscle
description: A single large dorsal limb rotator muscle in lower tetrapods that runs from the lumber region and girdle to the femur.

name: puboischiofemoralis externus muscle
description: A single large ventral muscle in lower tetrapods that runs from the pubis and ischium to the femur.

name: iliofemoralis muscle
description: Limb extensor that runs from ilium to femur.

name: patagialis muscle
description: A muscle of the patagium that attaches to the clavicle and the metacarpal

name: depressor mandibulae muscle
synonyms: ["depressor labi mandibularis","depressor labi mandibularis muscle","depressor mandibulae"]

name: levator operculi
description: Hyoid muscle that originates at the ventrolateral margin of the pterotic and inserts in the dorsomesial edge of the opercle. The levator operculi is responible for jaw depression, its force of contraction is transmitted through the opercular series and the interoperculo-mandibular ligament to the lower jaw.

name: ventral head of rib
description: Ventral head of a bicapitate rib. It articulates with the parapophysis.

name: dorsal head of rib
description: Dorsal head of a bicapitate rib. It articulates with the diapophysis.

name: diapophysis of neural arch
description: Paired processes that arise near the midpoint of the neural arch lamina, for the attachment of the tuberculum of two-headed ribs. Also called transverse processes. In anurans, the term diapophysis is used in reference to the modified transverse processes of the sacral vertebra elaborated for support of the pelvic girdle.

name: interclavicle
description: Dermal bone of pectoral girdle that is median and ventral in position.

name: dermal element of plastron
description: Fused ventral dermal element constituting the plastron.

name: epiplastron
description: Paired dermal bone that is part of the anterior region of the plastron. The epiplastron is found only in turtles..

name: entoplastron
description: A median bone at the anterior margin of the plastron.

name: hypoplastron
description: A paired plastron element that is in the posterior part of the plastron, anterior to the xiphiplastron and posterior to the hyoplastron

name: xiphiplastron
description: A paired plastron element that is in the posterior part of the plastron, posterior to the hypoplastron

name: carapace bone
description: Fused dorsal element constituting the carapace of a turtle shell.

name: peripheral plate of carapace
description: One of a series of bones around the edge of the carapace.

name: pleural plate of carapace
description: One of eight pairs of plates on the carapace, forming two rows adjacent to the peripheral plates.

name: neural plate of carapace
description: One of a series of plates on the dorsal midline of the turtle shell, posterior to the nuchal bone.

name: pygal plate of carapace
description: One of three plates on the posterior end of the carapace, posterior to the neural plates.

name: nuchal plate of carapace
description: The anteriormost plate of the carapace.

name: suprapygal plate of carapace
description: A plate that lies between the posteriormost neural plate and the pygal plate.

name: plastron scute
description: A scute that is part of a plastron.

name: carapace scute
description: A scute that is part of a carapace.

name: perichordal ring
description: Enlarged section of perichordal tube that is arranged serially but out of phase with segmental musculature.

name: subdivision of organism along main body axis
description: A major subdivision of an organism that divides an organism along its main body axis (typically anterio-posterior axis). In vertebrates, this is based on the vertebral column.

name: trunk vertebra
description: A vertebra in the trunk region. For tetrapods, includes lumbar and thoracic vertebrae. Excludes caudal/coccygeal vertebra, which are located posteriorly. In tetrapods this includes thoracic, lumbar and sacral vertebrae, and excludes the cervical vertebrae, which are located anteriorly.

name: hindlimb intermedium bone
description: A proximal tarsal bone that articulates with the fibula.

name: proximal tarsal bone
description: A tarsal bone that connected_to a hindlimb zeugopod skeleton.

name: adductor mandibulae
description: An adductor muscle that acts on the jaw. In some species, this is subdivided into segments based on attachment.

name: levator palatoquadrati
description: A muscle derivative of the mandibular levator that runs from the chondrocranium to the palatoquadrate cartilage. Found in sharks

name: preorbitalis muscle
description: A jaw muscle arises near the orbit and tapers as it passes posteriorly to its insertion on the adductor mandibulae. Found in sharks.

name: pre-enameloid
description: Odontoid tissue that is avascular non-mineralized matrix that is deposited by odontoblasts and ameloblasts that are excluded from the matrix.

name: enameloid
description: Skeletal tissue that is hypermineralized and aprismatic and deposited by a combination of ameloblasts and odontoblasts that are excluded from the matrix. Enameloid develops from pre-enameloid tissue.

name: embryo portion of umbilical artery
description: Each of the two arteries arising from the hypogastric arteries of the fetus and passing throught the umbilical cord to the placenta.

name: embryonic cardiovascular system
description: A cardiovascular system that is part of a conceptus.

name: midgut loop
description: Portion of midgut after it bends around the superior mesenteric artery

name: caudate lobe hepatic sinusoid
description: A hepatic sinusoid that is part of a caudate lobe of liver.

name: quadrate lobe hepatic sinusoid
description: A hepatic sinusoid that is part of a quadrate lobe of liver.

name: aortic valve leaflet
description: A cardiac valve leaflet that is part of a aortic valve.

name: pulmonary valve leaflets
description: A cardiac valve leaflet that is part of a pulmonary valve.

name: genital swelling
description: Paired structures in the embryo that represent the final stage of development of the caudal end of the external genitals before sexual differentiation. In both males and females the two swellings merge: in the female, they become the posterior labial commissure; In the male, they become the scrotum

name: female labial swelling
description: A genital swelling that is part of a female reproductive system.

name: male genital swelling
description: A genital swelling that is part of a male reproductive organ.

name: jugular lymph sac
description: An embryonic lymph sac that forms at the junction of the future internal jugular/anterior cardinals and subclavian veins.

name: left recurrent laryngeal nerve
synonyms: ["left recurrent laryngeal branch","left recurrent laryngeal nerve","vagus X nerve left recurrent laryngeal branch"]

name: right recurrent laryngeal nerve
synonyms: ["right recurrent laryngeal branch","right recurrent laryngeal nerve","vagus X nerve right recurrent laryngeal branch"]

name: cartilaginous projection
description: Anatomical projection that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: mentomeckelian
description: Paired, cylindrical, and small bones of endochondral origin that lie anteromedial to the anterior end of Meckel's cartilage. The precursors of the mentomeckelian bones are the larval infrarostral cartilages.

name: obsolete larval structure
description: Anatomical structure that is part of the larva.

name: lower jaw opening
description: An anatomical space that is part of a bone of lower jaw.

name: upper jaw opening
description: An anatomical space that is part of a bone of upper jaw.

name: utriculosaccular duct
description: A duct connecting the the utricle to the saccule in the membranous labyrinth of the ear.
synonyms: ["Böttcher's canal","ductus utricosaccularis","utricosaccular duct","utricosaccular duct of membranous labyrinth","utriculo-saccular duct"]

name: vagus nerve nucleus
description: A cranial nerve nucleus that is associated with a vagus nerve.
synonyms: ["nucleus of vagal nerve","nucleus of vagal X nerve","nucleus of vagus nerve","nucleus of Xth nerve","tenth cranial nerve nucleus","vagal nucleus","vagal X nucleus","vagus nucleus"]

name: dorsal commissural nucleus of spinal cord
description: A continuous column of gray matter along the midline in the dorsal gray commissure that sends fibers to the hypogastric nerve.

name: nucleus of spinal cord
description: A neural nucleus that is part of the spinal cord.

name: motor nucleus of vagal nerve
synonyms: ["motor nucleus of X","motor nucleus X","nucleus motorius of nervi vagi","nX"]

name: nerve of head region
description: A nerve that is part of a head.

name: feather follicle
description: A small tubular invagination of the skin with a fleshy dermal papilla at the bottom from which the feather grows. The papilla is inserted in the opening at the end of the quill. Forms by invagination of cylinder of epidermal tissue at base of feather bud.

name: feather follicle placode
description: An epidermal thickening above a condensation of dermal cells that will give rise to a feather follicle

name: feather shaft
description: The combination of the rachis and the calamus.

name: feather muscle
description: Similar to erector pili muscles of mammals; attached to the sides of the follicle; capable of elevating or lowering entire groups of feathers.

name: rectrix feather
description: A flight feather that lies along a single horizontal row on the rear margin of the anatomical tail. Only the central pair are attached (via ligaments) to the tail bones; the remaining rectrices are embedded into the rectricial bulbs, complex structures of fat and muscle that surround those bones. Rectrices are always paired, with a vast majority of species having six pairs. They are absent in grebes and some ratites, and greatly reduced in size in penguins

name: remex feather
description: A flight feather located on the posterior side of the wing

name: primary remex feather
description: A remex feather that is connected to the manus

name: secondary remex feather
description: A remex feather that is connected to the ulna.

name: tertial remex feather
description: A remex feather that is connected to the humerus.
synonyms: ["tertial flight feather","tertial remex","tertial remiges","tertiary flight feather","tertiary remex","tertiary remiges","true tertial"]

name: cavity of feather shaft
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a feather shaft.

name: dermal pulp of feather shaft
description: A tissue that is part of a cavity of feather shaft.

name: dermal condensation of feather follicle
description: A suprabasal cell population which together with the feather follicle placode develops into the feather follicle.

name: feather bud, dermal component
description: The part of the feather bud formed by a proliferation of dermal cells
synonyms: ["dermal core of feather papilla","dermal papilla","dermal papilla of feather bud","dermal papilla of feather papilla"]

name: feather bud, epidermal component
description: An epithelial bud that is part of a feather bud.

name: dermis of feather follicle
description: A tissue that is part of a dermis and is part of a feather follicle.

name: epidermis of feather follicle
description: A tissue that is part of a epidermis and is part of a feather follicle.

name: outer epidermal layer of feather follicle
inner epidermal layer of feather follicle
synonyms: ["epidermal collar","epidermal collar of feather follicle","follicle collar","follicle collar of feather follicle"]

name: collection of feathers
description: An anatomical cluster that consists of feathers.

name: non-neurogenic ectodermal placode
description: Ectodermal placode that does not develop into a component of the nervous system.

name: skin appendage placode
description: An ectodermal placode that gives rise to any of the cutaneous appendages that protrude from the skin epidermis (heair, feathers, epidermal scales).

name: superficial fascia
description: Superficial fascia is found in the subcutis in most regions of the body, blending with the reticular layer of the dermis. It is present on the face, over the upper portion of the sternocleidomastoid, at the nape of the neck, and overlying the sternum. It is comprised mainly of loose areolar connective tissue and adipose and is the layer that primarily determines the shape of a body. In addition to its subcutaneous presence, this type of fascia surrounds organs and glands, neurovascular bundles, and is found at many other locations where it fills otherwise unoccupied space. It serves as a storage medium of fat and water; as a passageway for lymph, nerve and blood vessels; and as a protective padding to cushion and insulate. Superficial fascia is present, but does not contain fat, in the eyelids, ear, scrotum, penis and clitoris.

name: lumen of atrioventricular canal
description: A tube lumen that is part of a atrioventricular canal.
synonyms: ["AVC lumen","cavity of atrioventricular canal","lumen of AVC"]

name: atrioventricular region
description: An anatomical junction that divides and overlaps with and atrium and a ventricle in the heart.

name: irregular connective tissue
description: Connective tissue, which consists of a population of connective tissue cells, the intercellular matrix of which contains an irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, mucoid tissue, connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.

name: dense irregular connective tissue
description: Irregular connective tissue is an irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a dense irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.
synonyms: ["irregular dense connective tissue","typus irregularis (textus connectivus collagenosus compactus)"]

name: dense connective tissue
description: Dense connective tissue is mainly composed of collagen type I. Crowded between the collagen fibers are rows of fibroblasts, fiber-forming cells, that manufacture the fibers. Dense connective tissue forms strong, rope-like structures such as tendons and ligaments. Tendons attach skeletal muscles to bones; ligaments connect bones to bones at joints. Ligaments are more stretchy and contain more elastic fibers than tendons. Dense connective tissue also make up the lower layers of the skin (dermis), where it is arranged in sheets

name: loose connective tissue
description: Irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a sparse irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, neuroglial tissue, mucoid tissue.

name: vestibular gland
description: Lobular organ the parenchyma of which consists of glandular acini which communicate with the vestibule of vagina. Examples: right vestibular gland, lesser vestibular gland.

name: areolar gland
description: A sebaceous glands in the areola surrounding the nipple.
synonyms: ["accessory gland of breast","accessory gland of Montgomery","gland of Montgomery","Montgomery's gland"]

name: duct of lesser vestibular gland
description: A duct that is part of a minor vestibular gland.

name: duct of vestibular gland
description: A duct that is part of a vestibular gland.

name: duct of sebaceous gland
description: A duct that is part of a sebaceous gland.

name: acinus of sebaceous gland
description: An acinus that is part of a sebaceous gland.

name: acinus of parotid gland
description: An acinus that is part of a parotid gland.

name: acinus of salivary gland
description: An acinus that is part of a salivary gland.

name: acinus of areolar gland
description: An acinus that is part of a areolar gland.

name: acinus of lactiferous gland
description: An acinus that is part of a mammary gland.

name: acinus of lacrimal gland
description: An acinus that is part of a lacrimal gland.

name: acinus of exocrine gland
description: An acinus that is part of a exocrine gland.

name: internal acoustic meatus
description: The internal auditory meatus (also internal acoustic meatus, internal auditory canal, and internal acoustic canal) is a canal in the petrous bone of the temporal bone of the skull that carries nerves from inside the cranium towards the middle and inner ear compartments namely cranial nerve VII and cranial nerve VIII.

name: aorta collagen fibril
description: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of aorta tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity

name: pulmonary collagen fibril
description: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of pulmonary tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity

name: bone collagen fibril
description: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of bone tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity

name: tendon collagen fibril
description: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of tendon tissue that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity

name: corneal stroma collagen fibril
description: The connective tissue bundles in the extracellular matrix of corneal stroma that are composed of collagen, and play a role in tissue strength and elasticity

name: condylar joint
description: In a condyloid joint (condyloid articulation, ellipsoidal joint) an ovoid articular surface, or condyle, is received into an elliptical cavity. This permits movement in two planes, allowing flexion, extension, adduction, abduction, and circumduction.

name: midcarpal joint
description: An intercarpal that connects a proximal and distal carpal bone

name: nasomaxillary suture
description: A cranial suture that connects a nasal bone and connects a maxilla.

name: synarthrosis
description: A synarthrosis is a type of joint which permits very little or no movement under normal conditions. Most synarthrosis joints are fibrous. Suture joints and synchondroses are synarthroses.

name: amphiarthrosis
description: Amphiarthrosis is a type of continuous, slightly movable joint.

name: ligament of sternoclavicular joint
description: A skeletal ligament that is part of a sternoclavicular joint.

name: body of tongue
description: The oral part of the tongue anterior to the terminal sulcus.

name: margin of tongue
description: The lateral border that separates the dorsum from the inferior surface of the tongue on each side, the two borders meeting anteriorly at the apex..

name: muscle layer of esophagus
description: A muscle layer that is part of a wall of esophagus.
synonyms: ["muscle coat of esophagus","muscular coat of oesophagus","muscular layer of oesophagus","tela muscularis (oesophagus)","tunica muscularis esophagi","tunica muscularis oesophageae"]

name: mesorchium
description: The testes, at an early period of fetal life, are placed at the back part of the abdominal cavity, behind the peritoneum, and each is attached by a peritoneal fold, the mesorchium, to the mesonephros.

name: anterior uvea
description: Front (ventral) portion of the vascular, pigmentary, or middle coat of the eye, including the ciliary body and the iris.
synonyms: ["anterior part of uveal tract","anterior uveal tract","anterior vascular layer of the eyeball","anterior vascular tunic of the eye","Haller tunica vascula","tunica vasculosa bulbosa","ventral uveal tract"]

name: endoneurial fluid
description: Fluid of the ganglia and peripheral nerves that lie outside the brain and spinal cord

name: lumen of vagina
description: A organ cavity that is part of a vagina.

name: endomysium
description: A layer of connective tissue that ensheaths a muscle fiber and is composed mostly from reticular fibers. It also contains capillaries, nerves and lymphatics. The term cardiac skeleton is sometimes considered synonymous with endomysium, but sometimes it refers to the combination of the endomysium and perimysium.

name: smooth muscle endomysium
description: Reticular tissue which surrounds a smooth muscle cell.

name: cardiac endomysium
description: Reticular tissue which surrounds a cardiac myocyte.
synonyms: ["endomysium of cardiac muscle cell","fibrocollagenous sheath of cardiac muscle cell"]

name: skeletal muscle endomysium
description: Reticular tissue which surrounds a skeletal muscle cell.

name: epimysium
description: Epimysium is a layer of connective tissue which ensheaths the entire muscle. It is composed of dense irregular connective tissue. It is continuous with fascia and other connective tissue wrappings of muscle including the endomysium, and perimysium. It is also continuous with tendons where it becomes thicker and collagenous.

name: perimysium
description: The fibrous sheath enveloping each of the primary bundles of skeletal muscle fibers.

name: gizzard smooth muscle
description: A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a gizzard.

name: gastrolith
description: A rock held inside a gastrointestinal tract.

name: plantaris
description: Plantaris is a vestigial structure and one of the superficial muscles of the posterior crural compartment of the leg. It is innervated by the tibial nerve (S1, S2) . It is composed of a thin muscle belly and a long thin tendon. It is approximately 2-4 inches long, and is absent in 7 - 10% of the human population. It is one of the plantar flexors in the superior compartment of the leg along with the gastrocnemius, and soleus. The plantaris is considered an unimportant muscle, it mainly acts with gastrocnemius.

name: muscle head
synonyms: ["caput (musculus)","caput musculi","head of muscle organ","muscular organ head"]

name: gastrocnemius medialis
synonyms: ["caput mediale (musculus gastrocnemius)","caput mediale musculus gastrocnemii","medial head of gastrocnemius","medial head of gastrocnemius muscle"]

name: gastrocnemius lateralis
synonyms: ["caput laterale (musculus gastrocnemius)","caput laterale musculus gastrocnemii","lateral head of gastrocnemius","lateral head of gastrocnemius muscle"]

name: cerebellar glomerulus
description: An intertwined cluster of nerve fibers surrounded by glia where mossy fibers from the pontine nuclei in the white matter synapse with granule cell axons, Golgi cell axons and unipolar brush interneuron axons

name: thalamic glomerulus
description: Synaptic structure found in thalamic relay nuclei consising of a complex of afferent terminals, relay cell dendrites, interneuron dendrites and other processes. These complexes are surrounded by astrocytic processes.

name: line of Schwalbe
description: The thickened peripheral margin of the vitreous membrane of the cornea.

name: yolk sac blood island
description: masses of developing blood cells attached to endothelium in the yolk sac
synonyms: ["visceral yolk sac blood island","yolk sac blood islands"]

name: connecting stalk blood islands
synonyms: ["blood island of umbilical vesicle","insula sanguinea vesiculae umbilicalis"]

name: cochlear basement membrane
description: The the continuous basement membrane found within the membranous labyrinth of the cochlea, known to extend from the limbus, down to the inner sulcus, across the basilar membrane, up to the external sulcus to the spiral prominence and radiating into the spiral ligament ensheathing the root cell processes
synonyms: ["basement membrane of cochlear labyrinth","cochlea basement membrane"]

name: postganglionic autonomic fiber
description: Nerve fibers which project from cell bodies of autonomic ganglia to synapses on target organs.

name: preganglionic autonomic fiber
description: Nerve fibers which project from the central nervous system to autonomic ganglia. In the sympathetic division most preganglionic fibers originate with neurons in the intermediolateral column of the spinal cord, exit via ventral roots from upper thoracic through lower lumbar segments, and project to the paravertebral ganglia; there they either terminate in synapses or continue through the splanchnic nerves to the prevertebral ganglia. In the parasympathetic division the fibers originate in neurons of the brain stem and sacral spinal cord. In both divisions the principal transmitter is acetylcholine but peptide cotransmitters may also be released.

name: postganglionic sympathetic fiber
description: A noradrenergic or adrenergic axonal fiber projecting from a sympathetic ganglion to an effector organ

name: preganglionic sympathetic fiber
description: A cholinergic axonal fiber projecting from the CNS to a sympathetic ganglion

name: postganglionic parasympathetic fiber
description: A cholinergic axonal fiber projecting from a parasympathetic ganglion to an effector organ

name: preganglionic parasympathetic fiber
description: A cholinergic axonal fibers projecting from the CNS to a parasympathetic ganglion

name: nasal hair
description: Hair in the nose
synonyms: ["hair of nose","hair of vestibular part of nose","nose hair"]

name: pilosebaceous unit
description: An epidermal invagination that has as parts a hair follicle, a sebaceous gland, and arrector pili muscle

name: vibrissa unit
description: A pilosebaceuous unit that contains a strand of virbissa hair (a specialized tactile hair) with the follicle incorporating a blood sinus, heavily innervated by sensory nerves.

name: vibrissa hair bulb
description: A bulb of hair follicle that is part of a vibrissa unit.
synonyms: ["bulb of sinus hair","bulb of vibrissa follicle","vibrissa bulb"]

name: vibrissa root sheath
description: A hair root sheath that is part of a vibrissa unit.
synonyms: ["root sheath of sinus hair","root sheath of vibrissa","root sheath of vibrissa hair"]

name: vibrissa inner root sheath
description: A hair inner root sheath that is part of a vibrissa unit.

name: vibrissa outer root sheath
description: A hair outer root sheath that is part of a vibrissa unit.

name: arrector pili muscle of vibrissa
description: An arrector muscle of hair that is part of a vibrissa hair.

name: lateral angle of scapula
description: An angle of the scapula that is broad and bears the glenoid cavity or fossa.

name: ureter luminal urothelium
description: A luminal layer of epithelium that is part of a ureter.

name: endometrium luminal epithelium
description: A luminal layer of epithelium that is part of a endometrium epithelium.

name: mammary gland luminal epithelium
description: The inner cell layer of the mammary epithelium bilayer that lines the luminal surface of mammary gland ducts and alveoli; luminal cells have only limited contact with the underlying basement membrane and surrounding connective tissue; they are secretory epithelial cells characterized by the expression of the receptors for systemic hormones, i.e. estrogens, progesterone and prolactin.
synonyms: ["lumina layer of epithelium of lactiferous gland"]

name: prostate luminal epithelium
description: A luminal layer of epithelium that is part of a prostate gland.
synonyms: ["subdivision of luminal layer of epithelium of prostatic gland"]

name: stomach glandular region
description: A region of the stomach that is lined with glandular epithelium.

name: stomach non-glandular region
description: A region of the stomach is lined with non-glandular epithelium. Examples of a stomach non-glandular region are found in rodents.

name: left hepatic vein
description: A hepatic vein that is part of a left lobe of liver.

name: right hepatic vein
description: A hepatic vein that is part of a right lobe of liver.

name: acetabular labrum
description: A ring of cartilage that surrounds the acetabulum.

name: glenoid labrum of scapula
description: A ring of fibrocartilage attached to the margin of the glenoid cavity of the scapula.
synonyms: ["glenoid labrum","glenoidal labrum","glenoidal labrum of glenohumeral joint","glenoidal labrum of scapula","labrum glenoidale"]

name: articular capsule of glenohumeral joint
description: An articular capsule that is part of the glenohumeral joint.
synonyms: ["articular capsule of humerus","articular capsule of shoulder joint","capsule of shoulder joint","fibrous capsule of glenohumeral joint"]

name: articular capsule of hip joint
description: An articular capsule that is part of the hip joint.
synonyms: ["capsula articularis coxae","capsule of hip joint","fibrous capsule of hip joint"]

name: transverse tarsal joint
description: The transverse tarsal joint is formed by the articulation of the calcaneus with the cuboid, and the articulation of the talus with the navicular. The movement which takes place in this joint is more extensive than that in the other tarsal joints, and consists of a sort of rotation by means of which the foot may be slightly flexed or extended, the sole being at the same time carried medially (inverted) or laterally.

name: talocalcaneonavicular joint
description: The talocalcaneonavicular articulation is an arthrodial joint: the rounded head of the talus being received into the concavity formed by the posterior surface of the navicular, the anterior articular surface of the calcaneus, and the upper surface of the plantar calcaneonavicular ligament. There are two ligaments in this joint: the articular capsule and the dorsal talonavicular.

name: calcaneocuboid joint
description: Calcaneocuboid Articulation (articulation of the calcaneus with the cuboid). The ligaments connecting the calcaneus with the cuboid are five in number, viz. , the articular capsule, the dorsal calcaneocuboid, part of the bifurcated, the long plantar, and the plantar calcaneocuboid.

name: saddle joint
description: In a saddle joint (sellar joint, articulation by reciprocal reception) the opposing surfaces are reciprocally concave-convex.

name: manubriosternal joint
description: The early union, by hyaline cartilage, of the manubrium and the body of the sternum, which later becomes a symphysial type of joint.

name: costotransverse joint
description: The facet of the tubercle of the rib forms an articulation with the adjacent transverse process of a thoracic vertebra. This is a plane type synovial joint called the costotransverse joint. This articulation is present in all but the eleventh and twelfth ribs. Ribs 1 to 10 have two joints in close proximity posteriorly; the costovertebral joints and the costotranseverse joints. This arrangement restrains the motion of the ribs allowing them to work in a parallel fashion during breathing. If a typical rib had only one joint posteriorly the resultant swivel action would allow a rib to be non-parallel with respect to the neighboring ribs making for a very inefficient respiratory mechanism. The ventral rami innervate the costotransverse joints. Therefore, therapeutic medial branch blocks are ineffectual. The ligaments of the joint are: Articular capsule Posterior costotransverse Anterior costotransverse Ligament of the neck of the rib Ligament of the tubercle of the rib

name: radio-carpal joint
description: A skeletal joint that connects a radius bone and connects a carpal skeleton.

name: mesotarsal joint
description: An ankle joint that passes between the proximal and distal tarsals.

name: talofibular ligament
description: A skeletal ligament that connects the fibula to the talus. Examples: anterior and posterior talofibular ligament

name: calcaneofibular ligament
description: A skeletal ligament that connects the fibula to the calcaneus

name: medial ligament of ankle joint
description: A skeletal ligament that connects a tibia and connects a tarsal skeleton.
synonyms: ["deltoid collateral ligament of ankle joint","deltoid ligament of ankle joint","ligamentum collaterale mediale (articulatio talocruralis)","ligamentum collaterale mediale articulationis talocruralis","ligamentum deltoideum","ligamentum deltoideum (articulatio talocruralis)","medial collateral ligament of ankle joint"]

name: epiphysis of phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a phalanx of a pes.

name: epiphysis of proximal phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a proximal phalanx of pes.

name: epiphysis of middle phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a middle phalanx of pes.

name: epiphysis of distal phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of pes.

name: epiphysis of proximal phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a proximal phalanx of manus.

name: epiphysis of middle phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a middle phalanx of manus.

name: epiphysis of distal phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manus.

name: crurotarsal joint
description: A joint that connects the bones of the crus to the proximal tarsal bones

name: manual digit 6
synonyms: ["6th finger","fore digit VI","fore limb digit 6","manual digit VI","sixth finger"]

name: manual digit 7
synonyms: ["fore digit VII","fore limb digit 7","manual digit VII","seventh finger"]

name: manual digit 8
synonyms: ["eighth finger","fore digit VIII","fore limb digit 8","manual digit VIII"]

name: pedal digit 6
synonyms: ["digitus sextus pedis","hind digit 6","hind digit VI","hind limb digit 6","pedal digit VI","pes digit VI","sixth toe","toe 6"]

name: infraorbital sinus
description: An air-filled recess in the head of birds which lies lateral to the nasal cavity into which it opens

name: mucosa of infraorbital sinus
description: A mucosa that adjacent_to a infraorbital sinus.

name: coelom
description: The aggregate of the coelemic cavity lumen plus the membranes that line the lumen.

name: myocoele
description: The cavity within a myotome

name: left lung lower lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a lower lobe of left lung.
synonyms: ["bronchiole of left lower lobe","bronchiole of left lower lobe of lung","left lung caudal lobe bronchiole"]

name: left lung upper lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a upper lobe of left lung.
synonyms: ["bronchiole of left cranial lobe","bronchiole of left upper lobe","bronchiole of left upper lobe of lung","left lung cranial lobe bronchiole"]

name: right lung lower lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a lower lobe of right lung.
synonyms: ["bronchiole of right cranial lobe","bronchiole of right lower lobe","bronchiole of right lower lobe of lung","right lung caudal lobe bronchiole"]

name: lobar bronchus of right lung middle lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a middle lobe of right lung.
synonyms: ["bronchus of right middle lobe","middle lobar bronchus","middle lobe bronchus"]

name: lobar bronchus of left lung upper lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a upper lobe of left lung.
synonyms: ["bronchus of left upper lobe","left superior lobar bronchus","left upper lobar bronchus","left upper lobe bronchus"]

name: lobar bronchus of left lung lower lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a lower lobe of left lung.
synonyms: ["bronchus of left lower lobe","left inferior lobar bronchus","left lower lobar bronchus","left lower lobe bronchus"]

name: primary bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that arises from a segmental bronchus and does not contain cartilage.

name: right lung middle lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a middle lobe of right lung.
synonyms: ["bronchiole of middle right lobe","bronchiole of right middle lobe","bronchiole of right middle lobe of lung"]

name: palatal tooth
description: A tooth that is on the roof of the mouth.

name: palate bone
description: Any bone that is part of a palate.

name: tooth of palatine bone
description: A tooth that is attached to a palatine bone.

name: bony part of hard palate
description: A subdivision of skeletal system that subdivision_of a hard palate.

name: replacement bone
description: Bone that forms as a replacement of another structural tissue.

name: tibiotalar joint
description: A skeletal joint that connects a tibia and connects a talus.

name: fovea capitis of femur
description: The surface of the head of the femur is smooth, coated with cartilage in the fresh state, except over an ovoid depression, the fovea of head of femur, which is situated a little below and behind the center of the head, and gives attachment to the ligamentum teres.
synonyms: ["fovea capitis","fovea capitis femoris","fovea capitis femoris (caput femoris)","fovea capitis of femoral head","fovea for ligament of head of femur"]

name: metapterygial axis
description: proximodistal trajectory through a metapterygium

name: patella cartilage element
description: A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a patella.

name: patella pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a patella.

name: bronchial lumen
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a bronchus.

name: lumen of primary bronchus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a main bronchus.
synonyms: ["lumen of main bronchus","main bronchial lumen","principal bronchial lumen"]

name: lumen of secondary bronchus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a lobar bronchus.
synonyms: ["lobar bronchial lumen","lumen of lobar bronchus","secondary bronchial lumen"]

name: lumen of tertiary bronchus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a segmental bronchus.

name: lumen of parabronchus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a parabronchus.

name: air capillary of parabronchus
description: An extension of the parabronchus, the walls of which are the site of gas exchange

name: appendicocostalis muscle
description: One of of three muscles associated with the uncinate processes.

name: perinatal stage
description: The period spanning the range immediately before and after birth

name: buccal salivary gland
description: A salivary gland that is part of a cheek.

name: suspensory ligament of breast
description: Cooper's ligaments (also known as the suspensory ligaments of Cooper and the fibrocollagenous septa) are connective tissue in the breast that helps maintain structural integrity. Transmission diffraction tomography can reveal the anatomy. Cooper's Suspensory Ligament should not be confused with the pectineal ligament (sometimes called the inguinal ligament of Cooper) which shares the same eponym.
synonyms: ["retinaculum cutis mammae","suspensory ligament of cooper","suspensory retinaculum of breast"]

name: sesamoid bone of the peroneus longus muscle
baleen plate
description: A keratinous sieve composed of bristles that enables filter feeding in the mouth of mysticete whales.

name: baleen plate bristle
description: A keratinous bristle that enables filter feeding in the mouth of mysticete whales.

name: postorbital bar
description: A strut formed from the union of the zygomatic process of the frontal bone with the frontal process of the zygomatic bone.

name: zygomatic process of frontal bone
description: The part of the zygomatic process consisting of the frontal bone
synonyms: ["frontal bone - zygomatic process","processus zygomaticus (os frontale)","processus zygomaticus ossis frontalis"]

name: frontal process of zygomatic bone
synonyms: ["processus frontalis (os zygomaticum)","processus frontalis ossis zygomatici","zygomatic bone - frontal process"]

name: diastema
description: A space or gap between two consecutive teeth.

name: ingested food
description: A substance that is consumed by the organism for food.

name: bolus of food
description: Ingested food has been chewed at the point of swallowing.

name: cud
description: A bolus of semi-degraded food regurgitated from the reticulorumen of a ruminant, produced during the physical digestive process of rumination

name: dental comb
description: A dental structure found in some mammals, comprising a group of front teeth arranged in a manner that facilitates grooming.

name: nutrient foramen conduit
description: Any of the passages admitting nutrient vessels to the medullary cavity of bone

name: lumen of nutrient foramen
description: An anatomical space that is part of a nutrient foramen conduit, leading to the medullary cavity of the bone.

name: infraspinatus tendon
description: The infraspinatus muscle inserts at this tendon to the distal greater tubercle of the humerus. This tendon stretches across the shoulder joint to attach to the humerus and in doing so acts as a very strong ligament to hold the joint surface in apposition. This structure restricts the movement of the shoulder joint to flexion and extension (together with the suscapularis tendon and the supraspinatus tendon). A bursa lies under this tendon at the greater tubercle of the humerus. The bursa is lined by a synovial membrance and filled with synovial fluid and protects the infraspinatus tendon and the shoulder joint by allowing the transmissions of tension and sheer forces around an angle.

name: vinculum tendon of wing
description: A tendon which emerges from the distal end of the humerus and follows the posterior margin of the wing, attaching at the distal end of digit 2. The raches of the remiges (i.e., the stems of the flight feathers) are stabilized by passing through the vinculum.

name: vinculum of tendon
description: A tendinous band that connects the phalanges and the flexor muscles of the autopods.

name: respiratory velum
description: A respiratory pump found in basal craniates

name: dermatological-muscosal system
description: Anatomical system that consists of the integumental system plus all mucosae and submucosae.

name: fibulare
description: One of two elements that constitute the basal row of tarsals. The fibulare constitutes the preaxial element.

name: feather barbicel
description: A minute hook that projects off of a feather barbule, holding barbules together

name: nose tip
description: Outermost point on an external nose or snout
synonyms: ["apex nasi","apex of nose","nasal tip","tip of nose"]

name: radial head of humerus
description: Hemispherical ball located at the lower end of the humerus that stands out prominently from the surrounding structures toward the flexor surface of the forelimb

name: olecranon fossa
description: A deep evacuation in the bone, into which the anconeal process of the ulna passes when the elbow joint is extended.

name: centrale
description: Endochondral bone located between the proximal and distal rows of carpals or tarsals and thus representing the central carpals or tarsals.

name: intercuneiform joint
description: The intercuneiform articulations are articulations among the cuneiform bones.

name: pedal digit 7
synonyms: ["hind digit 7","hind digit VII","hind limb digit 7","pedal digit VII","pes digit VII","seventh toe","toe 7"]

name: pedal digit 8
synonyms: ["digitus octus pedis","eigth toe","hind digit 8","hind digit VIII","hind limb digit 8","pedal digit VIII","pes digit VIII","toe 8"]

name: digitopodium region
description: A segment of the autopod consisting of both acropodial region and metapodial region, but excluding the mesopodial/basopodial region.

name: manual digitopodium region
description: A digitopodium region that is part of a manus. This includes the fingers and metacarpal region, but excludes the carpal region.

name: pedal digitopodium region
description: A digitopodium region that is part of a pes. This includes the toes and metatarsal region, but excludes the tarsals region.

name: skeleton of digitopodium
description: A subdivision of the autopod skeleton consisting of both acropodial skeleon and metapodial skeleton, but excluding the mesopodial/basopodial skeleton.

name: skeleton of manual digitopodium
description: A subdivision of the manus skeleton consisting of both manual acropodial skeleton and metacarpal skeleton, but excluding the carpal skeleton.

name: skeleton of pedal digitopodium
description: A subdivision of the pes skeleton consisting of both pedal acropodial skeleton and metatarsal skeleton, but excluding the tarsal skeleton.

name: buccal fat pad
description: The Buccal fat pad is one of several encapsulated fat masses in the cheek. It is a deep fat pad located on either side of the face between the buccinator muscle and several more superficial muscles. It should not be confused with the malar fat pad, which is directly below the skin of the cheek. It should also not be confused with jowl fat pads. It is implicated in the formation of hollow cheeks and the nasolabial fold, but not in the formation of jowls.

name: umbilical cord blood
description: blood that remains in the placenta and in the attached umbilical cord after childbirth.

name: core of nucleus accumbens
synonyms: ["core of nucleus accumbens","core region of nucleus accumbens","nucleus accumbens core"]

name: shell of nucleus accumbens
description: Crescent shaped outer zone of the nucleus accumbens, defined by a combination of chemoarchitecture and afferent and efferent connections. The shell is distinguished from the more centrally located core through the notable reduction in staining for the calcium-binding protein calbindin D28K, which is dense in the core and virtually absent in the shell.
synonyms: ["nucleus accumbens shell","shell of nucleus accumbens","shell region of nucleus accumbens"]

name: stomach primordium
description: A primordium that has the potential to develop into a stomach.

name: middle suprarenal artery
description: The middle suprarenal arteries (middle capsular arteries; suprarenal arteries) are two small vessels which arise, one from either side of the abdominal aorta, opposite the superior mesenteric artery. They pass laterally and slightly upward, over the crura of the diaphragm, to the suprarenal glands, where they anastomose with suprarenal branches of the inferior phrenic and renal arteries. In the fetus these arteries are of large size.

name: comb
description: A vascular, red cutaneous structure attached in a sagittal plane to the dorsum of the skull of domestic fowl. It consists of a base attached to the skull, a central mass called the body, a backward projecting blade and upward projecting points

name: skin apocrine gland
description: An apocrine gland that is part of a skin of body.

name: head or neck skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a craniocervical region.

name: tonsil crypt
description: Tonsils consist of an extensive system of crypts, which result in a large internal surface. The tonsils contain four lymphoid compartments that influence immune functions, namely the reticular crypt epithelium, the extrafollicular area, the mantle zones of lymphoid follicles, and the follicular germinal centers. In human palatine tonsils, the very first part exposed to the outside environment is tonsillar epithelium.

name: ovary growing follicle
description: An ovarian follicle undergoing maturation.

name: frontal artery
description: The supratrochlear artery (or frontal artery), one of the terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery, branches off where the ophthalmic travels posterior to the trochlea.

name: phrenic vein
description: The veins that run parallel to the phrenic arteries which include the two superior and two inferior phrenic veins.

name: superior intercostal vein
description: The superior intercostal veins are two veins that drain the 2nd, 3rd, and 4th intercostal spaces, one vein for each side of the body.

name: intercostal vein
description: The intercostal veins are a group of veins which drain the area between the ribs.

name: intercostal space
description: A space in the rib cage between two successive ribs.

name: posterior intercostal vein
description: The posterior intercostal veins are veins that drain the intercostal spaces posteriorly. They run with their corresponding posterior intercostal artery on the underside of the rib, the vein superior to the artery. Each vein also gives off a dorsal branch that drains blood from the muscles of the back. There are eleven posterior intercostal veins on each side.
